The triumph of right-wing populists in Austria: in total they have 29%
The perceptible weakening of both existing parties in the grand coalition and this marked strengthening of the populist right-wing parties led, according to the first provisional results, to early parliamentary elections on Sunday in Austria.
The Austrian People&#39;s Party (ÖVP), within which the position of current president Wilhelm Molterer is seriously faltering, has suffered particularly heavy losses.
In contrast, the electoral leader of the Union for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), Kärnten sub-prefect Jörg Haider, is preparing a triumphant return to national politics.
According to the provisional results, the strongest party in the country remains the socio-democratic one (SPÖ) with 29.8% of the votes, compared to the last elections in 2006, however it loses 5.5%.
It went even worse for ÖVP, who lost almost 9% of the votes with 25.6%.
These are the worst results of these two major parties in Austrian post-war history and above all the literally catastrophic result of the popular parties, which led to early elections.
Even at the beginning of July, when the ÖVP left the coalition, the populars had a significant advantage in preferences over the SPÖ.
But the voters evidently punished them because they scuttled the government.
Already in the first reactions to the results there were speculations about the possible resignation of the party president, Vice-Chancellor Wilhelm Monterer.
Observers believe that they could take place as early as Monday during the extraordinary convocation of the party leadership.
Perhaps this evolution should facilitate the path towards the increasingly probable way out of the electoral result, i.e. towards the renewal of the SPÖ and ÖVP coalition.
Regarding the strengthening of both right-wing populist parties - the liberals (FPÖ) gained early 18% and the BZÖ 11% of votes - but the socio-democrats simultaneously revealed the concern of another 1999, when the populists agreed with the popular collective government, (at the time the FPÖ was still united, in 2005 it separated from the BZÖ) which was even a reason for sanctions by the European Union.
Haider obviously plays on this evolution, who has already declared that he is ready to collaborate with any party and assumes a return to Vienna in national politics.
The Green Party also managed to enter Parliament, but it fell slightly, dropping from third to fifth place among the Austrian political parties.
No other party has evidently passed the 4% threshold and has not entered Parliament.
Duel to the death: MP3 players against mobile phones
We will advise how to choose
While almost any cell phone can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can make calls.
From this it becomes clear that it is better to just buy the phone.
Despite this, there are many reasons for which to get a standalone reader.
The choice depends entirely on the way of use and the needs of the future owner.
Perhaps you would hardly buy an expensive high-quality turntable to listen to Maxim Turbulenc&#39;s latest album on it.
First of all, these musical products are not released as LPs and from a qualitative point of view there is not even an objective reason for this.
However, if hard-rock, jazz or blues vinyls are crowded on your shelves, you probably dream of a turntable like this at least.
It also works with portable music, i.e. compressed music or simply in MP3 format.
Here, too, there are price and quality categories.
For some it may be unacceptable to spend 8,000 crowns on a player, just as a Pink Floyd fan may find it difficult to digest the twenty-crown headphones on the market.
Two extremes between which there is enough space for everyone.
The choice is wide.
It&#39;s the battery life that decides.
Some high-quality music players can do much more than just play music, but cell phones can&#39;t even accidentally.
There is no other device today as universal as the cell phone.
Alongside the primary functions, making calls and sending text messages, it can read music and videos, record both and has a camera, sometimes better, sometimes worse, and maybe it can even navigate.
And if we take smartphones and PDAs into consideration, you will also have a miniature computer in your pocket.
It&#39;s a small miracle since no refrigerator can grill and no television can photograph anything.
The universality of the mobile also brings disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your mobile, the sooner the indicator on the screen will ask for the charger.
And reading music consumes a lot of energy.
Few cell phones can read music for more than twelve hours, usually, and much less.
In this sense, music players (especially the simpler ones) are much more effective.
As for cheap cell phones, don&#39;t count that they can last for more than a few hours.
If you still add to it, from time to time, a few calls, get yourself another charger at work for safety, this also applies to the most expensive devices.
But you won&#39;t have this problem with an MP3 player, even the worst ones last at least 9 hours of continuous operation on a single charge.
Another problem arises when you download music to your mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have the universal USB port, and in addition, not all of them can be connected to a computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly to the memory card, but only a few memory players can do it without an adapter for minicards that are not used in cell phones.
Players, with some exceptions (Ipod) do not need any special software.
Simply fill the unit with music via USB from your computer.
Most mobile phones and players create themselves a media library sorted by artist names, album name, genre or user rating.
Some devices only reproduce the tree structure of folders, similar to the Explorer tool in Windows, and some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with OS).
Players are easier to handle, cell phones can do more.
When choosing a particular device, look first and foremost at battery strength, memory capacity, the quality and type of audio outputs, and of course ease of use.
If you need music above all as a background and if you listen to it only briefly every day on the tram, any mobile phone that can play MP3s will suffice.
This succeeds now, of course to any mobile phone.
You don&#39;t have to worry too much about which formats your mobile phone or player recognizes.
MP3 players support them all, the global majority of the music that comes to you will be in this format.
Apart from this format which belongs to the most popular ones, the total majority of devices support music in WMA format.
There is less AAC (format used by the Apple company and its Ipods).
The best cell phones also allow you, for example, to buy music online.
It is enough to visit, through the mobile Internet network, the corresponding pages of the operator (or other provider) and buy the song or album.
This same service could already be a valid argument for buying a mobile phone reader.
Unfortunately, the offer of the operators is meager and is usually limited only to hits of the moment on the radio.
The prices aren&#39;t exactly very low.
But it is generally assumed that this very way of selling music (whether via GSM, internet or wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their cell phones with them.
Anyone who wants to listen to a little something rummages in his pocket while the MP3 player remains forgotten at home.
However, this also depends on whether you always carry headphones or at least a wireless headset.
If not, you can use the built-in player that almost every cell phone, but only a small fraction of MP3 players, has.
Perhaps the biggest advantage of cell phone readers will be, for many, the price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than 3 thousand crowns.
For 3 and 4 thousand crowns you will already buy a very decent Walkman.
Usually, however, you will be limited by the lack of an input for common headphones.
The best and technically the most equipped mobile phones and even with the 3.5 mm socket for common headphones cost up to 15 thousand crowns.
Instead the advantage of the readers is, among others, the easy handling.
The simpler not necessarily cheaper ones (see our pick) really anyone can handle them.
The minimum of functions, the similarity of handling once with the common stereo or perhaps the record player, is obvious.
There is no danger of accidentally bumping up the mobile internet network and consequently a gigantic bill for data transmission.
Which appliance to get
Even the cheapest cell phones (for example Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable memory cards (type M2, microSD etc.).
Also for the purchase of the respective card, you are within the 2 000 crowns.
But be careful
Base models only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2GB.
Only the most expensive ones make it even with 8 GB memory cards.
If you already have a cell phone and want to buy an inexpensive MP3 player as well, get Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB) you shouldn&#39;t spend more than 1,100 kroner.
If you are part of the most demanding listeners, preferably take specialized mobile phones - walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have individual MP3 keys and the convenience of the service thus approaches the MP3 player itself.
In this area, Sony Ericsson has made the most headway, whose Walkman line phones have the same scale of use as MP3 players sold separately.
MP3 players of the above brands offer you the same service and price category up to 4 000 kroner, but with a larger memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (commonly 15 hours, usually maximum up to 35 hours).
The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic as early as this year.
Perhaps
Perhaps the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer practically all services like their partners in Western Europe.
However, something is missing here – a virtual operator who forces the traditional ones to lower the price.
Maybe it won&#39;t be missing for a long time.
We have already written many times on Mobil.cz about the fact that Czech operators belong to the most expensive ones in Europe.
After all, ČTÚ also confirmed it, pointing out that the price of SMS is higher in Italy than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulating roaming tariffs, perhaps a paradoxical situation will arise - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS will cost less from abroad than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that would really like to start the fight.
Perhaps it sounds absurd, even here we have three mobile networks and coverage well above 100%.
However, mobile phone operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this sense, the head of the Czech Telecommunications Council (ČTÚ), Pavel Dvořák, also often emphasizes, who in the past sometimes expressed that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with its own network probably doesn&#39;t have many possibilities anymore. (After all, perhaps it would be difficult to find other frequencies by now).
But there is yet another possibility - the virtual operator.
Just the entry on the market of virtual operators has led to a significant lowering of prices, to which traditional operators would then have had to react.
At the same time, even before the entry of sharks like Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile into the market, similar voices were resounding in Great Britain as here.
However, it has been shown that there is a place for such operators and that they can be truly successful.
After all, we don&#39;t have to go very far for examples.
In February of this year we informed you about the arrival of the Mobilking virtual operator in Poland.
In just half a year, this operator has managed to win over 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time behind Mobilking stands the financial group Penta which in the Czech Republic belongs among others to U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to actually function, it needs far fewer customers than a traditional operator.
They do not carry, that is, relatively high costs for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
Thus in the world virtual operators usually present themselves at a low cost, offering cheap calls and SMS, which is often in balance with the more restricted service offer
So for example Tesco Mobile in the UK offers text messages that cost at least half as much as its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, even betting on a significant target group can be a pretty good move.
This operator focuses specifically on men, so to speak.
&quot;Real men choose Mobilking operator they like and they can trust&quot; says David Seibertz CEO Mobile Entertainment Company which produces this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept can be affirmed here as in Poland.
Vodafone press spokesman Miroslav Čepický doubts it: &quot;The Czech market is relatively small for a fragmented approach, on which most virtual operators rely.
In addition, from the point of view of services, it is relatively saturated.&quot;
In the Czech Republic no chance, say mobile network operators
But it seems almost certain that if there is ever an operator in the Czech Republic it will not be Mobilking.
&quot;There is talk of expanding this successful project, but the negotiations in the Czech Republic are not full of expectations.
The ignition of Mobilking will rather take place in other countries in our area,&quot; Jana Studničková, the press spokesperson of the financial group Penta, said in a telephone conversation for Mobile.cz.
Thus he indirectly confirmed that the current traders in the Czech Republic are definitely not very supportive of this thought.
Quite the contrary, they try to do everything so that no potential competitor is created.
For some time now, it has not hidden its interest in starting a virtual operator, the GTS Novera group, which would thus like to take another step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónika O2 in the field of corporate customers.
&quot;We have a great interest in being able to offer our customers not only landline services but also mobile telecommunications.
And the sooner it is done the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile network operators.
We have already managed to make progress in negotiations with some of them,&quot; says group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
So maybe better times will come.
From unofficial information it emerges that we will have to have the first virtual operator perhaps by the end of the year.
For now, however, an impenetrable wall of silence rises around his creation.
&quot;Right now we don&#39;t believe that there is room in the Czech market for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
Until now, no person with a complex and serious project has approached us,&quot; Vlastimil Sršeň of the press section of Telefònika O2 mentioned in his statement to Mobil.cz.
The other operators also make use of the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobil press spokeswoman Martina Kemrová adds in rare agreement with the O2 statement: &quot;So far, we have not noticed any viable and mutually beneficial commercial project on which it is possible to continue building.&quot;
And he adds: &quot;It is unlikely that a virtual operator will appear in the T-Mobil network by the end of the year.
By now we should have already had a concrete agreement on the table, in order for it to be possible to consider it on the horizon.&quot;
Vodafone focuses its attention rather on meeting its 3G license requirements.
Miroslav Čepický adds: &quot;We are open to negotiations on potential virtual operators, especially in the area of sharing costs and infrastructure.
We consider this, from the point of view of customers, the most productive.
Vodafone&#39;s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common network for fast mobile internet.&quot;
The competent authorities - with the accomplice operators
The attitude of the mobile telephony operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, it would lead to a lowering of prices and with this a decrease in profits.
Why then facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The annoyances surrounding the U:fon creation testify that when operators care about something they know how to row on the same side.
Perhaps the great pressure was on ČTÚ in the period of creation of U:fon to the company of T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by the publicly accessible information from the ČTÚ web pages.
But right now U:fon serves as an argument for not accepting the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted: &quot;The competitive environment of the mobile telephony market was recently boosted above all with the entry of the fourth mobile operator in the market.
With regard to the type of mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another competitor would place high demands on it and above all on its services.&quot;
However, the complete lack of interest on the part of the Czech regulatory bodies is surprising in the attitude of the mobile telephony operators.
It is not just the attitude of the ČTÚ which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike Great Britain and other developed countries - has no competence to interfere in economic competition.
That belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
However, this has assumed its typical position in relation to the whole problem.
&quot;The entry of the virtual operator on the mobile telephony market would be possible after the conclusion of the contract for the rental of the necessary infrastructure between the mobile operator and the virtual operator.
No such contract has been concluded so far because the offer of potential buyers has probably not been interesting enough for the traditional operators,&quot; said Kristián Chalupa, of the ÚOHS External Relations Section, in response to our question.
Such a worded statement by the operators&#39; representatives is perhaps not surprising.
On the other hand, on the part of the office which has to defend the interests of consumers and above all ensure that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, it is more than a delicate affair.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: &quot;Abroad where virtual operators commonly operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to the lowering of prices for mobile telephony services.&quot;
But obviously the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the lowering of prices are not in the interests of ÚOHS.
Truly shocking in the whole situation is the almost emotional harmony of these three operators resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence arises by itself.
Just as the identical price of petrol for all petrol stations is certainly the result of coincidence and competitive struggle.
&quot;The section has found no signs of anti-competitive behavior regarding this fact and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No operator has a dominant position, therefore it does not have a corresponding greater responsibility for its behavior on the market.
The tools needed to open up the mobile network market for virtual operators may also be missing from the telecommunications regulator,&quot; Chalupa mentioned in his statement.
The interpretation of market dominance is one of many controversial points.
Of course there is the analysis of the relevant markets elaborated by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications are the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
On such a market, of course, no Czech operator has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer another approach - the agreement of the network operator is always required for the creation of a virtual operator.
And the mobile operator has – ultimately logically – a monopoly of its network.
So for a certain portion it must be dominant by force.
But even if we didn&#39;t admit this argument, it should be a little alarming to ÚOHS that three mobile operators proceed in such an eerily similar way.
At the same time the complaints from interested parties (including the mentioned company GTS Novera) show that during negotiations with all operators they encounter very similar obstacles.
Offloading responsibility to ČTÚ in telecommunications is a fairly frequent trick by which ÚOHS stays out of the whole thing.
We have already seen this in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it was not possible to promote the expansion of ČTÚ&#39;s rights in the field of economic competition in telecommunications until the recently approved update of the Telecommunications Law, despite the fact that many experts expected the situation to improve from this.
This fact the representatives of ÚOHS must know more than well, but perhaps their interests lie elsewhere.
It can be done, when no one is watching
While without our realizing it, the functioning of these pseudo-virtual operators remains, some of which even exist in Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that publish their own price lists for mobile telephony services which, however, are only partially public.
Usually these are companies that deal with multilevel marketing.
So for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only the pre-specified people.
The magic lies in the fact that the company appears to the operator as a classic corporate customer, who orders a large number of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he then receives special price offers (and more).
The problem is that the trading conditions of all Czech mobile operators forbid such pre-sales.
&quot;If the cases you mention arise, which we will look into, it could be a violation of the contractual conditions, and could lead to the conclusion of cooperation with this company&quot;, replied Martina Kemrová to the question in question.
But it is highly unlikely that such an activity did not reach the ears of the responsible subjects of mobile telephone operators.
Especially in the cases of the 3 companies mentioned, there can be thousands of customers.
No operator defends himself against such an attitude at the same time.
In other words, they derive a considerable profit from the activity of these companies and at the same time - unlike real virtual operators - they are not damaged in any way by their official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns about possible problems: &quot;The law permits such speculation, yet only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They also have to accept that the SIM card in their phone is not registered in their name, so they cannot have full use of it like regular customers of mobile phone operators&quot;
But this should be the least bit strange to the ČTÚ.
In addition, another question opens up for ÚOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such an attitude, why are they blocking the creation of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that ÚOHS has strong enough rights to unmask similar activities and if it does not want to, it will not have to settle for the explanation of operators who have no idea of all this and that their commercial conditions forbid it.
When we won&#39;t be more expensive
As has already been said several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators on the mobile telephony market has brought about a considerable reduction in the prices for services.
At the same time in practically all countries where operators were born, traditional operators tried more or less to prevent their creation.
The arguments they used were practically identical - market too small, borderline too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
But in developed countries it was precisely in these cases that the regulatory bodies intervened in defense not of the mobile telephone operators but of their customers.
With both formal measures and non-formal pressure, then the first virtual operator was created and others followed.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are throwing the whole case from one to the other like a hot potato.
In our experience, we cannot get rid of the feeling that the lack of clarity of competences in these cases is more than convenient for them.
But let&#39;s not throw in the towel.
If the information behind the scenes is correct and the virtual operator will appear with us really soon, the Czech mobile phone market will get back on its feet.
If one of the operators had consented to the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it would be difficult for ÚOHS to remain impassive to the refusal (discrimination) of the other interested parties.
And maybe we will stop calling at higher prices than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best one
Listen to four new versions of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem &quot;Kde domov můj&quot; on the occasion of the Czech State Recognition Day.
The new recording of the anthem was made by the orchestra of the National Theater under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available – solo with male or female voice, choir passage and the instrumental edition.
The singing is under the direction of Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the revisions of the anthem are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz website you can listen to all four versions.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song one of the most beautiful anthems.
Earlier he told the radio &quot;Český rozhlas&quot; that he specially chose to sing the solo variants, singers with the most representative young voices, who are expressive and popular.
&quot;From the beginning I have tried to make sure that both, and also the choir, have clear diction, that the text is well understood, that they are in harmony,&quot; he said.
Then the national anthem will celebrate the 175th anniversary next year.
The song &quot;Kde domov můj&quot; was first performed in 1834 on the stage of the Stavovskéh divadlo in Josef Kajetán Tyl&#39;s original opera Fidlovačka accompanied by music by František Škroupa.
It gained popularity and people spontaneously embraced it.
The first verse of the song after the founding of Czechoslovakia in 1918 then became the natural part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the birth of the autonomous Czech Republic.
