The Sudeten Germans in 1945 demanded that Šumava be included in the United States.
This results from the letter deposited in the Scientific Library of South Bohemia.
If we can&#39;t be part of Germany or Austria, we want to at least live under the patronage of the United States.
With this desire, according to reports, some groups of Sudeten Germans addressed the US president in 1945.
This emerges above all from the letter preserved in a private archive and today deposited in the Scientific Library of Southern Bohemia.
The Germans of Český Krumlov ask in the letter to the American president not to allow again the return of the &quot;Šumava district&quot; – occupied by Hitler on the basis of the Munich agreement – to Czechoslovakia.
&quot;We understand the situation and we want to be sure of the promises that the American units will arrive on German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators,&quot; the letter reads, signed with the words &quot;The people who care for the fate of Šumava with all the heart&quot;.
Since, they say, annexation to Czechoslovakia - knowing the Czech national character - gives the Sudeten Germans hope only for brutality, inconsiderateness, incomprehension, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter pray to the American president to assume the protectorate over Šumava now and forever.
&quot;We cannot believe that without regard for the opinion of a quarter of a million inhabitants, you would recognize this territory as a state alien to us, which oppresses and eradicates ethnic minorities and has contributed nothing, absolutely nothing, to the victory of the Allies,&quot; the letter writes.
The reason why the authors cannot sign it is the alleged fear of the &quot;Czech oppressors&quot; thirst for revenge.
If the US president doubts the conviction of the Germans of Šumava, it would be enough to organize a referendum in the district on the willingness of its inhabitants to become part of the USA or live under US control.
While the text of the letter may seem naïve with our knowledge of postwar history, according to some witnesses it aptly describes the expectations of Sudeten Germans at the time.
Even if the Czech Germans must have guessed at all that it would be their displacement from the republic, only a few of them admitted such a possibility at all.
Some expected the United States and Britain to negotiate some sort of autonomy for the peoples of the Sudetenland.
Others believed they would simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is also confirmed by the famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice.
He was mobilized during the war as a German from Budějovice in the Baltic Sea Power.
When he was captured by the British at the end of the war and placed in a POW camp at Holštýn, dozens of other Czech Germans came to see him to teach them Czech.
&quot;They thought the Czech would come in handy when they got home,&quot; Chalupa said.
According to him, none of the German prisoners who had lived in Czechoslovakia before the war counted on the fact that on the basis of Beneš&#39;s decrees they would be removed from the Republic.
