Turkey is broadening its diplomatic horizons
Long before Turkey sought to join the European Union, European powers were eager to penetrate deep into the Turkish hinterland.
On the eastern side of the Bosphorus, perhaps 20 paces into Asia, lies one of the finest relics of this failed imperial ambition.
Hydarpasha train station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in a neo-Renaissance style.
At least that&#39;s what the guidebooks tell you.
The building straddles the end of the platforms with a tower on each of its corners looking at the world like some German provincial town halls.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building slightly run down.
But once inside the vaulted ticket office, there&#39;s no doubting the magnitude of the enterprise of what used to be the westernmost passageway.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, the Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, a latecomer to the imperial game, wanted to realize its ambitions of dominating the Middle East by means of this railroad that ran to Damascus, Baghdad and beyond into what is now Saudi Arabia.
But Germany&#39;s imperial ambitions foundered during World War I.
Its railways were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arab irregulars.
Its relative isolation from the surrounding region, spawned by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has passed
British and domineering forces advanced out of Egypt and drove the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And there was bad news for Hyderpasha Station as well.
In 1917 an ammunition train exploded destroying its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then it has slowly fallen apart, largely overtaken by history.
But nowadays, this rail outlet to Anatolia and all points to the east serves - at least symbolically - to highlight Turkey&#39;s ever-widening diplomatic horizons.
The ruling Justice and Development party - the AKP - has created a whole new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from its surrounding regions, engendered by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has passed.
There is now a new engagement policy.
Remarkably, the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran and of course with the European Union and the United States.
To estimate the parameters of this new foreign policy, I boarded the sleeping car for the Turkish capital Ankara, to visit one of the AKP&#39;s leading foreign policy experts, Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a bumpy ride along the tracks that produced the old-world cadences of the famous documentary The Night Mail, I arrived in the Turkish capital - proposed as a new city for a secular state bent on turn away from its Ottoman past.
But the AKP with its well-known Islamic roots represents an exemplary shift in the Turkish consensus.
It has prompted some suspicions in the West, most notably in Washington.
A taxi takes me to the AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern structure of stone and steel - purpose-built - in a developing suburb, surrounded by half-built shopping malls and power bakeries, where business-suited managers - both men and women - meet to make contracts in the early morning.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a centre-right politician from almost any other political party in Europe.
Suit, tie, I&#39;m sure he had a Blackberry too.
&quot;The aim of the foreign policy party now is to reintegrate Turkey with its closest neighbors.
The Cold War was an anomaly,&quot; he tells me.
Turkey has been cut off from its hinterland.
Today it has to look east and west at the same time.
It wasn&#39;t the case for one or the other.
It must be both.
&quot;But surely at some point,&quot; I ask, &quot;Turkey will be forced to decide?&quot;
&quot;Turkey,&quot; he says, &quot;doesn&#39;t want where to make that choice.&quot;
He then underlines a point that almost everyone I spoke to here recited by heart: the ties of not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus, and all around the Black Sea, benefit Europe and the United States as much as they are for Turkey.
With Turkey on board, the message seems to be, All of Europe can metaphorically run those train lines eastward through Asia and into the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpasha station, after another sleepless night, I think of those two German gentlemen Herr Ritter and Herr Conu who had looked at this building built 100 years ago.
