In a separate city, pride and trials of a black life
Tucked away in the sprawling theme park on the Orlando suburbs, just miles from the splendor, the noise, the huge, lies the quiet city where the pride and complications of the African-American experience come into life.
Eatonville, the first all-black incorporated city in the country and the birthplace of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer quite as simple as she described it in 1935: &quot;the city of five lakes, three croquet lawns, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, plenty of guava, two schools and no jail.&quot;
Now it is a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Zora! Festival at Eatonville to show their respects to Hurston, the most famous writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
Yet in many ways, the city it described—and which makes tourists stop by including it in the Florida travel guide produced by the Depression-era Federal Writers&#39; Project—remains a place apart.
She is as independent, dignified, and private as she was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted sharing their thoughts with the white man, who &quot;knowing so little about us, doesn&#39;t know what he&#39;s missing.&quot; .&quot;
Even now, in a year where a black presidential nominee, Senator Barack Obama, has been called in to keynote address on race, many here remain wary of the outsider&#39;s gaze.
&quot;We are very careful about how our story is told,&quot; said Hortense Jones, 59, a lifelong resident and member of the city&#39;s oldest church.
&quot;It has to be right.&quot;
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and hardship.
It is both a historic model of black takeover and a community of nearly 2,400 where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a literary center but also an oak-shaded example of rural Southern black culture - sometimes scorned, sometimes rewarded - born out of American slavery.
Not surprisingly, the residents here are both proud and protective.
And the concern for Eatonville&#39;s image really began with Zora, whom everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced the world to her hometown through earnest, dialect-rich books such as Mules and Men (1935) and Their Eyes Were Watching God (1937).
Five paragraphs of the Florida guide transformed the city, just off Rout 17, a road that runs through the oft-forgotten center of Florida into a backdrop of black history and human drama
Low as a bass drum in both life and literature, Hurston took readers to the shop owned by Eatonville&#39;s first mayor, Joe Clarke, then detoured into more private areas.
&quot;Off the road to the left,&quot; he wrote, &quot;is the modern public school, brown with white trim, with its well-kept gardens and courtyards, which Howard Miller always tended, thinking he could scarcely read and write.&quot;
She also mentioned Widow Dash&#39;s new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn &quot;sells drinks of all kinds and whatever fits the walk-through rooms.&quot;
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston connected Eatonville with self-government but also with illiteracy, remarriage and sex.
Clearly this was not Fodor&#39;s.
Indeed, it was not a portrait that everyone appreciated.
&quot;Zora was saying it like it was,&quot; said Ella Dinkins, 90, one of Johnson&#39;s girls whom Hurston immortalizes by quoting men singing crass songs about their beauty.
Adds: &quot;Some people don&#39;t like it.&quot;
Hurston is still remembered here as a vivacious eccentric who frequently returned to her family who moved to Jacksonville, Fla.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalls that when Hurston swooped into town, he routinely arrived unannounced in a triumphant Chevrolt, smoking and wearing slacks in a city that even today prides itself on decent dress.
Many residents were fascinated, Mr. Franklin says, while others chuckled.
&quot;People were always very happy to see Zora,&quot; Mr. Franklin said.
But, he added, rocking back in his chair on the back patio overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, &quot;she never stayed long.&quot;
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books had gone out of print.
Along with the rest of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten her.
Though she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes, and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Fla., where she had lived.
In Eatonville, there were no big memorial services, and no big conferences.
&quot;I don&#39;t think they understand his contribution to the world or his legacy at all,&quot; said Valerie Boyd, author of &quot;Wrapped in Rainbows,&quot; a biography of Hurston published in 2003.
A change came in the 80s.
Orange County officials wanted to lay a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the two-lane main road.
Orlando&#39;s expansion has already pushed Interstate 4 through the city&#39;s western limit.
The proposal came when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had ended the community&#39;s relative idyllic isolation
In the 1950s, the battle over miscegenation brought hatred to the community&#39;s doorstep.
&quot;During that time, a bunch of white kids came and threw oranges and things at the people sitting on one side,&quot; says Mr. Franklin.
&quot;We actually had a girl who was killed by that one time.
They threw a watermelon from a car.&quot;
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston made a request to the Supreme Court for forced integration, calling his decision in Brown v. Board of Education &quot;an insult rather than an honor to my race.&quot;
Residents now say the desegregation of the schools, while they have been positive in some respects, dilutes Eatonville&#39;s cohesion and threatens the confidence of its young people.
&quot;Black kids used to be hugged — I remember this — you hugged your teacher in the morning, you hugged your teacher at night,&quot; said NY Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and the executive director of Preserve the Eatonville Community, a non-profit group.
This lasted, he added, until teachers and students came from the same place.
&quot;You didn&#39;t hug your white teacher because your white teacher…- I mean, there&#39;s a cultural divide there,&quot; Ms. Nathiri said.
Civil rights, however, helped and made room for many more Zora Neale Hurstons - black writer, actress and artist who overcame prejudice, as she did, with cheerful self-confidence and lines like, &quot;How can some deny themselves the pleasure of my company!
I just can&#39;t understand.&quot;
In 1975, writer Alice Walker set out on a long journey to Hurston&#39;s unmarked grave and began fighting for the resurrection of her reputation.
Five years later, an acclaimed biography of Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway hit bookstore shelves, reintroducing it into the American canon.
The freeway project came just as its most famous daughter had re-entered the limelight.
And this time, Hurston&#39;s old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The community began planning a Hurston festival in 1988 to show what could wreak havoc on the state with its highway.
Thousands of fans came to the inaugural event two years later, and every January, many return for the commemoration.
Many years later, the state backed out of its road plan.
&quot;The five-lane resurrected highway has brought what one would say high speed, a real pride for the city,&quot; said Ms. Nathiri.
Mrs. Boyd puts it simpler: &quot;Zora saved Eatonville.&quot;
Victory over the highway project has helped change the city&#39;s self-image.
Out-of-towners like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who began coming to church here in 1993, began appearing in large numbers, and residents began to reevaluate the past.
Eatonville was added to the public historic register in 1998.
A new single-story bookstore (named after Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on a repaved and beautified Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: Just six miles from downtown Orlando, it can feel like a back street in the summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded with just 27 black families in the 1880s.
(She&#39;s 90 percent black today.)
Outsiders who come to seek out Eatonville&#39;s history, for its significance, are often still treated with caution.
Advance permission is required for most interviews, but some things—like the murals on Eatonville&#39;s oldest church, painted by a white man, showing black men in the fields—aren&#39;t allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Ms. Jones, a plump schoolteacher with a penchant for bright red, still fear their island community is being misunderstood.
Yet as the Hurston festival has expanded, a high level of city pride has also emerged.
Young people, especially, tend to see Eatonville with Hurston—she saw her entire race: beautiful, troubled and all, no better, no worse, and proud and creative and hard working and foolish and confused like other races and ethnic groups in America.
Genuine civic affection can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin&#39;s nephew, Edwin Harvey, 18, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in local government or for the Police Department, which he said may need of help.
And even those who are younger, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, 11-year-old twins from Winter Park, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
&quot;A lot of people, if they&#39;ve just walked in here, will think, &#39;Oh, this town is nothing compared to all the others,&#39;&quot; said Alondra Kenon after mass on a recent Sunday.
&quot;But if you really stop and take a moment to look at the history, it really is a lovely city.&quot;
Here in New York we are all fluent in finance
On the surface, nothing has changed.
If tourists in Manhattan stayed away from the newspaper stands and huge television screens of Times Square, they wouldn&#39;t realize they were in the eye of the storm.
They would never guess that the glass offices, honeycombed over their heads bankers and hedge fund managers who monopolize New York every day experience the worst &quot;bad day at the office&quot; since the crash of 1929.
Bellhops shake metal tea carts across the sidewalks, carrying trays of muffins for breakfast meetings.
Latin Americans shuffle between apartment buildings carrying, like human mules, 50-odd pressed shirts hung on a stick on their backs.
Office workers still wait in line for their morning bagel at sidewalk food carts, and it&#39;s still impossible to catch a yellow cab between 4 and 7 pm on a workday.
It didn&#39;t seem like there was a real crisis, until, with all the talk of doom and gloom, I decided to open a new savings account on Thursday afternoon.
Although I had timed the affair to coincide with the late afternoon break at my JP Morgan Chase branch, a queue of about twenty was already waiting in line.
Not in front of the cashier&#39;s desk, to withdraw money or make deposits, but in front of the customer service desk, where old customers order checkbooks, tourists ask for directions to Macy&#39;s Department Store, and new customers open accounts.
Many of those ahead of me, I would later learn from Starr, my &quot;trusted banker,&quot; were in line for the same reason as me.
Unlike me, however, they&#39;ve already pulled savings from smaller banks from places they commute from, such as those in New Jersey, Pennsylvania and Staten Island.
They have taken the money from so-called thrifts (sort of like a construction company), credit unions and city savings bank types whose branches operate only within a state, and they say they treat customers like family .
In the past year, 15 of these banks have gone bankrupt.
In recent days, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion in assets, has been placed into receivership, and as New Yorkers headed home for the weekend on a Friday afternoon, another bank, Wachovia, with savings deposits of $440 billion, was looking for a buyer to bail it out.
The clerks and clerks who stood before me, fearful of another collapse, were moving their money to a bank perceived as a safe haven, the bank that is bailing the most on Wall Street.
Ordinary New Yorkers have become proficient in finance in recent weeks.
A woman at my favorite Chinese supermarket, speaking on the phone, referred to Lehman Brothers, the bank that went bankrupt, and its emaciated CEO Dick Fuld in all familiarity, as if complaining about a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the nearly 50-year-old uniformed concierge at my apartment building, changed the subject from our normal topic of conversation about Brad and Angelina or my grocery delivery.
She told me, after my visit to the bank, &quot;Now I have all my savings in market funds!.
I changed, I&#39;m not taking any risks.&quot;
Lives Remembered: Vernon Handley and William Woodruff
Mark Brown writes: As Guildford Music Director from 1962, Vernon &quot;Tod&quot; Handley (obituary, 11 September) was in charge of the Guildford Philharmonic Orchestra and Chorus.
As a member of his music scheme for the municipality, he founded his own wonderful youth choir, Proteus, the following year.
They were supposedly under-21/under-21, but by the time the Proteus sang its finale in 1979, many of us were well into our twenties - we simply refused to give up the chorus.
The name &quot;Proteus&quot; (the mythological mutable-being) represented the willingness of the choir and the ability to tackle anything the music presented to do, whether madrigals or Messiaen, unaccompanied or with full orchestra.
The musical versatility produced by such a young choir was often astonishing, always exciting, and it was all due to that man&#39;s inspiration and enthusiasm for music which remained absolutely constant through the years.
How often we were told by Tod to &#39;let the music speak for itself&#39;.
He had said: &quot;The composer knows what he wants.
It&#39;s all there in the music.
So sing it!&quot;
His technique in using the wand was absolutely clear and precise, though never dictatorial or flowery.
Whatever the musical standard, he raised it higher and higher.
John Frayn Turner writes:
If one conductor were to be knighted it would be Vernon Handley.
I knew him very well during the two decades he conducted the Guildford Philharmonic from 1962 to 1982.
Over the past 40 plus years I have watched over 100 of his concerts and can honestly say I have never disagreed with a single one - and many times been inspired by them.
Tod Handley had that rare combination of personal grandeur and modesty.
He hated conductors who, in his words, simply &quot;rode around the world a well-known workhorse or two.&quot;
He will be missed by so many of us.
William Woodruff
Professor John Beckett writes:
Your obituary for William Woodruff (September 25) specifies that &quot;in 1946 he resumed studying economic history at Oxford and in 1950 became a research fellow at Houblon-Norman ... studying at the same time for a science, an arts and a PhD&quot;.
This follows from Woodruff&#39;s author&#39;s note in Beyond Nab End, but is incorrect.
From 1946 to 1953 he was a lecturer in economic history at the University of Nottingham, during which time he completed a PhD thesis on the British rubber industry, supervised by Professor JD Chambers, and subsequently published in 1958 as The British Rubber Industry.
He spent 1950-51 in the USA as a researcher at Houblon-Norman, and the summer of 1952 at the universities of Illinois, Harvard and New York.
In 1953 he left Nottingham permanently for Illinois.
Why Woodruff chose to cover this part of his career is unknown.
Muslim graves desecrated as Austria turns right.
Heinz-Christian Strache, left of Austria&#39;s right wing Freedom Party and Filip Dewinter of Belgium&#39;s right-wing Vlaams Belang party take part in a rally to present the organization &#39;Cities against Islamisation&#39; in Antwerp on Thursday 17 January 2008.
They carry signs like road signs representing mosques with a red line running through them.
Police have blamed right-wing extremists for desecrating a Muslim cemetery in Austria, the same week that far-right political parties gained big in the national general election.
More than 90 graves were badly damaged at the Traun cemetery near Linz in a few hours between Friday night and this morning in what police believe was an organized action.
The perpetrators spray-painted Jewish symbols such as the Star of David on some graves, but detectives believe it may have been an attempt to disguise extremist motives driven by a hatred of Muslim immigrants.
It is not clear whether the incident is related in any way to the election.
A spokesman for the local Islamic community said they were &quot;deeply shocked&quot; by news of the desecration, which occurred towards the end of Ramadan, a month of religious significance for Muslims.
Austria meanwhile has embarked on a journey of spiritual quest following its rightward shift in yesterday&#39;s parliamentary elections.
The two far-right parties that took nearly 30 percent of the vote, the Austrian Freedom Party and the Alliance for the Future of Austria, campaigned with vehemently anti-immigration tickets and some of their slogans were defined by xenophobic critics.
Heinz-Christian Strache, the head of the Freedom Party which won more than 18 percent of the vote, has campaigned against headscarves and burkas and has also voiced his opposition to foods that are perceived to be connected to Islam.
At the final rally in Vienna, he spoke of a &quot;European brotherhood&quot; to prevent the growth of Islam.
Both parties appear to ban the building of mosques and minarets, arguing that they are political symbols of a continued Islamization of Austria and Europe.
Polls and analysis done immediately after the elections, which established the far right as the nation&#39;s strongest political bloc, indicated that the change was being driven predominantly by young voters who are concerned about their future in the European Union.
Travel abroad forbidden to Gary Glitter.
Gary Glitter, the glamorous rock star convicted of child sexual abuse, has been banned from traveling to France and Spain by the court.
Magistrates imposed a six-month ban on Glitter after he informed the authorities supervising him that he wanted to travel to Spain via France.
The ban on overseas travel was granted to Kent Police last Thursday after they provided prosecutors with evidence of previous arrests of Glitter for child sexual abuse.
Glitter, real name Paul Gadi, was not present at the hearing at Ashford Magistrates Court in Kent but was represented by Corker Binning&#39;s solicitors.
A Court Service spokesman said: &quot;On Thursday 25 September at Ashford Magistrates Court, Kent Police lodged an application to prevent Mr Paul Gadd&#39;s overseas travel to France and Spain until 25 March.
&quot;Paul Gadd was not present in person.&quot;
Glitter, 64, had informed authorities that he wanted to travel abroad as required by the register of convicted sex offenders.
He must notify the authorities if he wishes to travel abroad for more than three days.
He is also required to give the police seven days notice of his intended departure date.
Failure to notify the authorities can lead to a five-year prison sentence.
Kent Police said they did not want to discuss individual cases or Glitter&#39;s possible travel around the country.
A Kent Police spokesman said: &quot;Kent Police will do whatever is necessary to protect children in this country or abroad.
&quot;From our point of view, it&#39;s easier to screen someone who stays in the UK because we have comprehensive systems in place to manage any potential risk more effectively.
&quot;Protecting Kent residents is the primary concern of Kent Police and we work closely to monitor the behavior of convicted sex offenders registered in the country to minimize any possible risk to the public.
Glitter returned to the UK last month after spending 27 months in a Vietnamese prison for abusing two girls aged 10 and 11.
When Glitter came he flew to Bangkok where he was supposed to board a flight to London.
But he said he felt ill and refused to fly to London.
The Thai authorities would not let him through passport control and he eventually took a flight to Hong Kong.
The Chinese authorities also did not let him in and he returned to Bangkok where Thai police and immigration officials insisted that he return to England.
He finally arrived at Heathrow Terminal 3 on 22 August and remained there while his solicitor David Corker went to Uxbridge court, west London, as Scotland Yard had successfully applied for an order to place him in the convict register. for sexual offences.
Glitter was previously jailed in the UK in 1999 for possessing images of child abuse.
A Home Office source said Jacqui Smith, the Home Secretary, was reassured and delighted that Glitter had been stopped from traveling to France and Spain.
&quot;I photograph the master away from the scene to extract his character&quot; Günther Bauer, photographer
Neither heels nor ruffles nor premiere dresses.
Only the essence of the great flamenco masters, stripped of the concentration that characterizes the interpretation, to look at the relaxed appearance of the man or woman.
On the one hand the artist.
On the other, the person.
Two inseparable faces, except in private, in those moments away from the public, when the intimacy of a gesture, the depth of a stolen gaze or the expressiveness of the hands, are natural because they don&#39;t have to go on stage.
The German Günther Bauer in &quot;Flamenco-People&quot; alternates the theatricality of some shots of singers, dancers and guitarists on stage with the lesser-known side of these masters.
With this lens, the photographer offers an original iconography of flamenco, capturing it from different visual angles.
The exhibition, included in the Flamenco Photography Month program, reflects the international importance of this dance, which is growing every day,&quot; explains the artist and clarifies that in &quot;Flamenco-People&quot; it could also be ordinary people, but seeing the photos, the viewer realizes that they are not typical images of artists or performers on stage.
These people portrayed &quot;on the street&quot; are &quot;artists capable of transmitting passion, sadness, joy when they are on stage ... and captivating the public.
To grasp the personality of these greats it is not necessary to portray them on stage,
because their personality and character are internal.
What interested me was to create an intimate atmosphere that would allow me to capture the personalities of flamenco greats on camera.&quot;
With a passion for the &quot;Cante de las Minas&quot; festival, Bauer began in 1997 a long journey aimed at portraying singers, guitarists or dancers using a plate camera.
They are portraits which, due to the type of camera and the material, are reminiscent of classic photography.
The application of different stylistic techniques breaks with the traditional principles of the image, giving the photo modernity, according to an idea that reflects Bauer&#39;s own conception of flamenco: &quot;A music with very traditional roots that evolves and is able to surprise every day.&quot;
Not the dancing, singing or playing itself, but the personality of the artist, his character, capable of conquering the public with his art.
The search for an encounter with the essential elements, with the magic that becomes visible in a certain way of feeling and being, are and have been the constant of this work, on display these days at the El Fotómata gallery.
Famous flamenco artists such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, feature in this selection of around seventy portrait artists.
The project has become a sort of anthology of flamenco, and will soon be published in a book that will collect the portraits exhibited at the exhibition.
The passion for portraits led Bauer to repeat the idea two years ago with &quot;Portraits of Veteran Athletes&quot; (&quot;SportARTproject&quot;).
Although in &quot;Flamenco-People&quot; the concept is different, the photographer admits &quot;I love portraying people, getting to know them and being able to penetrate their lives for a moment, be it a long or short moment.
I think portraiture is the most difficult genre in photography.
You meet or confront people, characters you sometimes don&#39;t even know or who only give you a few minutes to take the picture.
Regardless of these circumstances, like a photographer, I always try to materialize my ideas.&quot;
The collection of portraits of contemporary flamenco, entitled &quot;Flamenco-people&quot; is set up at the El Fotómata gallery, at number 20 in via de la Mata, parallel to via Alameda de Hercules, and will be open to the public until next October 16th.
Vargas Llosa reveals that the novel he is writing is a &quot;gambling&quot;
It&#39;s set in places he doesn&#39;t know yet and deals with unknown topics: despite this, Mario Vargas Llosa is grappling with a new project he&#39;s working on, a novel whose protagonist, Roger Casemant, is an Irish nationalist who lived twenty years in the Congo and crossed the Amazon.
Always favored for the Nobel Prize for Literature, the writer confessed yesterday at the Hay Festival in Segovia that the project he is working on today &quot;is a gamble&quot; and that &quot;everything indicates that I shouldn&#39;t write it.&quot;
&quot;If I had common sense, I wouldn&#39;t write it, but I will do it anyway and I hope to finish it as soon as possible,&quot; concluded his speech at the festival for the exchange of ideas, thoughts and words that for four days he saw passing through the city of &#39;Aqueduct a hundred writers, historians, journalists and thousands of people.
The author of &quot;La ciudad y los perros&quot; was, as expected, the leading figure at the third edition of the festival of the word.
Vargas Llosa, who won the Hay Festival&#39;s prize for being the most voted writer by attendees – an early edition of Dickens&#39; &#39;Our mutual friend&#39;, filled the seats at the Juan Bravo theatre.
Presented by Félix Romeo, the writer found himself in front of an audience whose time flew by when the Peruvian, with a prodigious memory and large doses of humor, recalled how the literary vocation was born in him, derived from the &quot; extraordinary adventure&quot; of the &quot;pleasure of reading&quot; and &quot;of living beyond what I used to live&quot;; as he writes in a &quot;disciplined way&quot; to make up for the &quot;lack of inspiration&quot;, with an intense work of documentation, editing and continuous remaking; how Faulkner, Victor Hugo and Alexandre Dumas influenced his vocation and how &quot;the images of memory&quot; are the basis on which his stories are based.
The Spanish-American novelist acknowledged that &quot;there is no way&quot; to measure and know if books can change people&#39;s lives, &quot;but I refuse to believe that literature is pure entertainment, an ephemeral experience, &quot; underlined Vargas Llosa, arguing that, on the contrary, &quot;it has effects&quot; and that &quot;it makes people more nonconformist.&quot; This is why he invited writers not to &quot;give in to frivolity&quot; and to &quot;take responsibility&quot; for their own vocation.
The weather hampers the Pozoblanco Festival, depriving it of bullfights
The bullfighting celebration that was supposed to seal the days of the Pozoblanco Festival was suspended yesterday morning, after the bullfighters selected for the bullfights had verified that the soil conditions of the square were not adequate.
Therefore, the company, in agreement with Fermin Bohorquez, Pablo Hermoso de Mendoza and Leonardo Hernandez, has decided to suspend the celebration of bullfighting.
The bad weather has raged against this Festival preventing us from celebrating two days out of three.
On Saturday, rain prevented the second bullfight from taking place.
On the bill were Jose Luis Moreno, Curro Diaz and Juan Bautista, who were due to face a Castilblanco bull.
Therefore, the Festival was held regularly only on Fridays.
On this occasion it was Daniel Luque who triumphed, cutting off three ears and being carried out in triumph, after bullfighting with taste and aesthetics.
That same afternoon, Alejandro Talavante completed his two bullfights, earning greetings and an ear, granted more by the public than by the bullfight itself.
The worst of all was El Juli, passing from the Los Llanos arena ingloriously and without penalty.
With the second bull, after a tremendous muleta, he earned the boos of a large part of the public.
A van with two thousand kilos of hashish passes the checkpoint in Alava
Five to ten in the morning.
The agents call a halt to the two occupants of a van who, instead of stopping, flee.
The agents ordered a halt to the two occupants of a van who, instead of stopping, fled.
Their load, more than two tons of hashish, is a good reason not to stop.
After chasing them, the agents manage to arrest one of the two occupants, a man of around 28, identified as AAJ, according to a statement from the Basque government&#39;s Interior Department.
The arrested individual is charged with drug trafficking and falsifying public documents.
The incident occurred when Alava road officials were carrying out a transport check on the N-1, where it crosses the municipal district of Armiñón.
They were about to stop a van for inspection when the driver, defying orders, accelerated sharply and passed the checkpoint.
The agents gave chase until the vehicle, after a couple of kilometres, stopped at the side of the road and its two occupants fled into a wooded area.
The Ertzaintza agents then succeeded in arresting one of the fugitives and seizing the 2,178 kilograms of hashish they were carrying. Once they inspected the van, they took note of it, an Iveco Daily.
