&quot;Sangre de mayo&quot;, Garci&#39;s epic wager
Inspired by Benito Pérez Galdós&#39; Episodios Nacionales, Jose Luis Garci re-proposes in Sangre de mayo the famous revolt of the Spaniards against the French, in what is the most ambitious film in his filmography, with a budget of almost 15 million euros.
With this film, the director has attempted to &quot;illustrate the torrent of characters and at the same time the social analysis&quot; that he has always admired in the work of the famous novelist, he explained today during the presentation of the film, starring Quim Gutierrez and Paula Echevarría at the head of a large cast of performers.
Sangre de mayo, more than two and a half hours long, debuts this Friday in cinemas, to eventually become a television miniseries of more than four hours on TeleMadrid.
A great admirer of Galdós&#39; literature, Jose Luis Garci claims that with this film he has made &quot;a dream of his childhood&quot; come true, and believes he has to thank Esperanza Aguirre, who from the Community of Madrid had commissioned him three years earlier to shoot a commemorative film for the second centenary of 2 May medrilegno. The director agreed on the condition that the story be based on the novel Episodios Nacionales.
The 15 million budget allocated in full by the Community of Madrid represented a &quot;unique opportunity&quot; for Garci to recreate the appropriate sets and costumes to portray a &quot;a stunned Spain that made the wrong choice of leader to fight for and the fact that the struggle for independence brought the people a huge delay in development under the reign of Ferdinand VII,&quot; noted Garci.
However, the director regrets not having received the same funding as Alatriste or Los phantasmas de Goya - more than double that of Sangre de mayo, so it was not possible to shoot some scenes foreseen by the scenography that he himself had signed together to Horacio Valcarcel, a collaborator of almost his entire career.
For the director of Volver a empezar, this influenced what is his usual working practice, staging with actors, with whom he often rehearses before shooting together with those who will not be part of the cast, because he considers it &quot;humbling,&quot; considering that &quot;part of a director&#39;s job is going to the theater and the cinema to find out what&#39;s happening in the industry in which he works.&quot;
Many of the performers, some of whom are part of the cast of Sangre de mayo, rehearse in front of his camera, as in the case of Michael Rell, Carlos Larranaga or Fernando Guillen Cuervo.
Nominated for an Oscar four times - winning one - Garci believes that none of the three films nominated to represent Spain at the Hollywood Academy this year - his Sangre de mayo, Siete mesas de billar francés and, last selected Los sunflowers ciegos -, do not represent the younger generation of Spanish cinema &quot;which should be known instead.&quot;
Garci does not expect awards from this film.
&quot;At first you think you&#39;re working for posterity, then you realize you&#39;re only working for prosperity, and at some point you settle down to just making one more film,&quot; explains Garci after more than 30 years of career.
