Microsoft is looking for (virtual) receptionists
At the MIT conference on emerging technologies, Microsoft previewed a new image recognition and human interaction system, a kind of artificial intelligence, but without much intelligence, capable of performing some basic tasks, such as calling a taxi (or, in Microsoft&#39;s case, a shuttle service to get around the company&#39;s campus) by assisting the telephone user.
Thanks to a camera and a shape and face recognition system, this &quot;receptionist&quot; is able to know how many people are in a room, who they are - including remembering their position in the company - and to listen and understand the keywords in a conversation with them.
It can also group attendees into conversation groups.
In the example video, the receptionist detects a third person, but realizes that she does not belong to the group she is speaking to and that she is not an employee of the company.
He asks her if she&#39;s there to visit someone and tells her he&#39;ll be available to her shortly.
