But this, of course, is the future.
Now the company has better things to focus on, like the next version of its Windows operating system.
There has been a lot of talk this week about a change in strategy at Microsoft.
Windows 7 will be lighter and won&#39;t have as many associated programs.
Steve Ballmer has discovered that if computers were equipped with the essentials and less loaded with commercial junk, they would go five times faster – hey! Steve, it will be for &quot;the least&quot;.
All a discovery, if we consider that Microsoft, version after version has continuously added features and &quot;extras&quot; to Windows.
The change of direction is appreciable.
Microsoft is right: the operating system is increasingly losing importance, and with it the software.
When Google launched Chrome on the net, I was one of those who supported the theory that it was Google&#39;s first step to compete with Windows.
