Second assault for Honda supersales
In November, Honda will start marketing the second generation of the Jazz model.
If the previous model was already equipped with great habitability, this new minivan has an even larger interior space.
To all must be added a refined mechanics, which increases driving comfort and allows you to save fuel.
Evolution versus revolution.
This is the second generation Honda Jazz.
Although aesthetically the new Jazz has a line very similar to that of the previous model, the changes in this minivan are numerous.
Among others, it is worth noting an innovative design, a new platform, larger dimensions and new mechanics.
However, before moving on to analyze the new model, it is useful to note that this new Jazz arrives six years after the first generation entered the market.
Therefore, a first observation is that Honda has renewed this model in a shorter time than those used by other manufacturers.
Although the Jazz model is less known in Europe than in other markets, it remains a unique sales phenomenon.
This is exactly the case in Japan, where the Jazz was the best-selling car in 2002 and again in 2008.
Almost one million units of the Jazz have been sold in Japan since its launch.
The second market was that of the Old Continent, with around half a million units in six years.
Despite these numbers, Honda believes that the new Jazz will help increase sales in the segment.
Thus, if in 2007 the Japanese company sold a total of 83,000 units of this model, for 2009 the estimates are around 100,000 cars, assuming a 17% increase in sales in the European market.
As for the Spanish market, Honda has sold a total of 8,000 Jazz units since 2002, which corresponds to 6.7% of Honda&#39;s total sales in Spain.
As for the new generation, those responsible for the Spanish branch expect to sell around 2,000 units of Jazz over the course of a year.
Just the arrival of the new Jazz will allow Honda to significantly reduce the decline in sales in Spain.
In fact, company executives expect to end the year with a total of 22,000 units sold, or 4,000 fewer than in 2007, a drop of 16%.
Despite the increase in sales Honda increased its market share in Spain, reaching 1.8%, compared to 1.6% last year.
Furthermore, the Japanese company expects to reach 2% in 2010.
To achieve this, Honda is confident in the arrival of another new model.
This is Insight, a five-door hybrid and compact format - 4.37 meters long - of which the Japanese company hopes to sell around 200,000 units a year worldwide.
For the markets and according to estimates made by the Japanese manufacturer, 50% of Insight sales will take place in the United States, while the remaining percentage will be divided between the Old Continent and Japan.
The commercial launch of the Insight is scheduled for the first few months of the year, immediately after the company presentation in January in Valencia.
Compared to the first generation, the new Jazz has grown in all its parts.
Its length reaches 3.90 meters (five centimeters more), the width 1.69 meters (two centimeters more) and the wheelbase 2.50 meters, with an increase of five centimeters.
The height, however, remained unchanged at 1.52 metres.
Along with the increase in size, the living space also expands.
This advantage derives on the one hand from the inclusion of a new platform, and on the other from the introduction of the fuel tank in a central position, a solution also adopted in the previous Jazz model.
Furthermore, the luggage compartment capacity - equipped with a double background - rises to 399 litres, ie 19 liters more than the capacity of the first generation.
It should be noted that these are the measurements of the 1.4 engine version, and that the boot capacity of the Honda Jazz 1.2 is 379 litres.
Other improvements - in addition to external elements, such as the rear LEDs or the possibility of mounting the panoramic glass - concern an improvement in terms of accessibility to the rear seats.
The doors that allow access to the rear positions, in fact, open at an angle of 80 degrees, compared to 67 degrees on the first Jazz.
Furthermore, the engines in this second generation of the jazz are also new.
At the time of marketing, this small model will be offered in models with 1.2 and 1.4-litre petrol engines.
Both mechanics include i-VTEC technology which makes it possible to lower fuel consumption, produce fewer carbon dioxide emissions, optimize the mechanics and at the same time keep the engine torque high in all its phases.
The 1.2-litre model allows you to take advantage of a power of 90 HP at 6,000 rpm with a maximum torque of 114 Nm at 4,900 rpm.
The propulsion - which in the previous Jazz reached 78 horsepower - uses 5.3 liters of fuel and produces CO2 emissions of around 125 grams.
Compared to the previous propulsion, which used 83 horsepower in the first generation model, 100 are now available.
The 100 horsepower Jazz 1.4 achieves a combination of 5.4 liters of fuel and 128 grams of CO2 emitted.
