The &quot;ape car&quot; to avoid collisions
As part of the development of technologies for accident prevention, Nissan has been inspired, this time, by nature, and in particular by bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, taking the flight of bees as an example, knows how to avoid accidents.
It is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which is the first step towards collision avoidance technologies.
Engineers from the Nissan Motor Co. Advanced Technical Center developed this small robot in collaboration with the Science and Technology Research Center of the prestigious Tokyo University in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, director general of Public Relations for Technology and Brand Management Research and Development, the BR23C is an extension of Nissan&#39;s four-area Safety Shield.
This robot is intended to improve the ability to avoid collisions in manufacturer vehicles.
During flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space that is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
But most important are the bees&#39; compound eyes, which are able to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees, and which allow the insect to fly without interruption in its personal space.
To recreate this visual functionality, engineers devised what they termed a laser range finder.
This mechanism identifies the obstacles that are in front of the BR23C for a radius within two meters and with a maximum width of 180 degrees, calculates the distance from the object and sends a signal to an on-board microprocessor which immediately allows prevent collision.
&quot;The moment it senses an obstacle, the little robot mimics the movements of a bee and immediately changes direction by turning its wheels at a right angle or greater to avoid a collision.
The most obvious difference with any assisted system is that the evasion maneuver is totally instinctive.
&#39;If this were not the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,&#39; explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and lead engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot swerve up or down, or even diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction in which its wheels can turn and not taking advantage of infinite directions and ways as bees do.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, as well as acceleration and deceleration, so that the little robot can avoid collisions.
&quot;This device just needs to process information every few seconds, and act on that data.
It doesn&#39;t require memorization of information or the intuitive logic of previous maneuvers, so it can run without interruptions and with only a couple of dozen KB of memory.
This may come as a surprise, but we&#39;re not talking gigabytes of storage, or even megabytes.&quot;
It is the first step in developing new technologies for instantaneous collision avoidance, a technology Nissan hopes will be standard in automobiles within ten years.
The robot uses lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and more durable than lithium-ion types.
Another potential future application of this technology could be integrating the units with a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to their destination while avoiding obstacles in their path.
Drivers who repeat alcoholism will have to install the &quot;alcolock&quot;
The Ministry of the Interior requires drivers with three administrative fines for excessive blood alcohol levels to install a system in their car that prevents driving while intoxicated or if one does not blow into the device.
The provision was announced last June and is already included in the annual report of the State Attorney General&#39;s Office, according to which it will be a one-year pilot project.
The aim of this project is the reintegration of the driver, since he will have to attend a road rehabilitation course.
In addition to the Public Prosecutor&#39;s Office for Road Safety, the General Directorate of Traffic (DGT) and the Technological Institute for Automobile Safety Foundation (FITSA) will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of motorists reported more than once for driving while intoxicated then go back to driving the car.
The alcohol lock would avoid this, because it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the level of alcohol in the exhaled breath and prevents you from starting the car if the driver does not blow, or when a higher alcohol concentration is detected than that allowed.
The cost is more than 1000 euros and would be borne by the sanctioned person.
In this regard, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with these devices allow for a reduction of up to 65% of infringements committed during the first year of introduction.
And in Spain it is estimated that it could save the lives of 115 people a year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to curb these behaviors before they become criminal offences.
And to facilitate its development, since the legal reform can be carried out in the ordinary way, and, undoubtedly, the reform necessary for the penal procedure would require an organic law.
However, the device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial solution, even if it has already been introduced on an experimental basis in some industrial and public vehicles.
Just tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on an initiative by the PSOE in which it is proposed to install this system in school buses, as has already been done in France.
