Sleep talking
Some children talk during the night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very agitated to tell us something that happened to them the previous day, but to those children who talk while remaining asleep.
The first time it happens, at best you get a scare, but it really doesn&#39;t matter much.
It is a benign sleep disturbance called somniloquy.
It occurs with a certain frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Of course, most of you have been told that you talked in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (once in a lifetime, for example associated with an episode of high fever) or more regularly (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the next day the child no longer remembers anything.
There is no single reason that can explain this phenomenon.
Sometimes they are episodes connected to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night terrors, nocturnal enuresis (wetting the bed), or sleepwalking, but this is not necessarily the case.
As already mentioned above, it can be associated with very high fever stages, stressful or overexcited situations.
In any case, it is still a little-studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also extremely variable.
It may happen that the person speaks in a very calm tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper or that the opposite occurs (screams, shouts, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, it would be advisable to observe the child and possibly consult a specialist to check if there is any issue that is generating an anomalous state of anxiety as an outlet for the situation.
We have said that it is a benign alteration therefore there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (for example, if coupled with insomnia or a stressful situation).
What can be done, however, is to take into consideration a series of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to overexcite the baby before he goes to sleep.
Offer calm games and avoid programs or television series that arouse fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children who find it difficult to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them gain some inner calm.
This will allow the baby to sleep more peacefully.
Once the sleep talkers appear try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember anything that happened.
Useful tips
Don&#39;t wake him up.
It&#39;s useless, because he&#39;s not aware of what&#39;s happening, and you&#39;ll interrupt his sleep.
Although he is talking, he is sleeping and therefore resting.
Remember that if he appears very anxious and the episodes have a certain frequency it is better to consult a doctor or check where such great anxiety in the child comes from.
If you understand what he&#39;s saying (which isn&#39;t the most common situation), don&#39;t be tempted to interrogate him for information.
You will get nothing, because he is asleep and therefore unconscious to organize his thinking.
Additionally, you are able to hear what he says but not see what he is dreaming to say it, so you need to be very careful in interpreting the information and the conclusions it might lead to.
Never tell the child that you could ask him questions during the night to learn his secrets.
Not even as a joke.
Such a thing causes enormous distress.
In short, don&#39;t worry, it&#39;s nothing serious, it&#39;s an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
