Héma-Québec yesterday celebrated the tenth anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Dr. FrancineDécary, had every reason to rejoice, as Héma-Québec has become one of the safest blood suppliers and effective in the world.
And above all, he regained the trust of the public, seriously shaken by the scandal of the infected blood in the years between 1980 and 1990.
As we know, the national blood supplies managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected by the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus in the 1980s.
Faced with such a tragedy and protests by the population, the Government of Canada conducted a public inquiry in February 1994, directed by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to disseminate recommendations to prevent a similar disaster from happening again.
While Judge Krever was slow to issue a report, some provinces set up a committee to devise a new blood management system in Canada.
In Québec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau committee.
Following the Gélineau et Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Québec and the Société canadienne du sang (Canadian Blood Society) for all other provinces and the two territories.
In 1998, when Héma-Québec began its activities, just 38% of people said they still had faith in the donation system in Québec, recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was mortifying.
Thanks to continued efforts to improve the safety of blood sampling and field research over the ensuing years, we have regained the public&#39;s trust,” she explains before proudly stating that as of early 2008, approximately 94% of the population of Québec he now had faith in Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary is convinced that &quot;trust is something extremely fragile&quot;.
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, the Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were numerous cases of the human variant of mad cow disease in Europe, a new manifestation of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says the woman who has been its president since 1998, the year it was founded.
&quot;And we absolutely didn&#39;t know if that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
We therefore based ourselves on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports, according to which when there are doubts and a serious illness could result, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease which manifests itself with a degeneration of the brain that leads inevitably at death, measures of exclusion are adopted.
In April 1999, blood was refused from those who had spent more than a month in the UK since 1980.
Now, for some years now, it has been demonstrated that this disease is undoubtedly transmitted through infected blood.
This episode has thus shown us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle.&quot;
In 1999, a much more efficient technique for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid test (TAN) which allows the presence of the virus to be recognized directly in the blood of donors and not that of antibodies against it. on which the tests used until then were based.
The TANs have made it possible to reduce the window period, i.e. from the moment the person contracted the disease to the moment in which the first viruses can be identified in the blood thanks to our techniques, explains the specialist.
It was possible to reduce that period to less than a week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and therefore not being able to identify them is thus significantly reduced.
These improvements have made it possible to considerably decrease the risk of contracting AIDS with a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving blood infected with the HIV virus.
&quot;In other words, this means that 12 million blood samples will need to be distributed before anyone is infected with the HIV virus.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood samples each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmitted by transfusion is found.
I believe that today we can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover our health, says the head of the Héma-Québec management.
&quot;Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know what pathogen will emerge in your system.
As recently as a year ago, Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like West Nile virus, is transmitted in the blood by an insect.
You have to be constantly vigilant&quot;, continues Dr. Décary before emphasizing that in addition to having safe resources, Héma-Québec must also ensure that they provide enough.
&quot;Needs increase as the population ages.
As the most aggressive cancer treatments, patients often need a supply of red blood cells or platelets.
The aging of the population also has consequences for the number of donors, which on average constitutes only 3% of Québec inhabitants acceptable as donors.&quot;
However, all healthy people over the age of 18 who meet the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer themselves as donors are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where the latter is widespread, they will be refused for a period of one year .
&quot;With this 3% we are able to maintain an inventory capable of responding to the needs of hospitals.
Cases of shortages are very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor group as they get older and can no longer donate.
Now it is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to keep them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Life is so hectic nowadays that there is hardly an hour to donate blood,&quot; says Francine Décary desolately.
With an annual budget of 297 million dollars, Héma-Québec not only distributes blood samples, but also human tissue, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before being deposited at the Héma-Québec which operates the only public cord blood bank in Québec.
In the umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, there is an abundance of blood rich in stem cells which can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
&quot;We celebrated the bank placement of our 1,000th cord blood sample a few weeks ago and expect to collect more than 1,000 each year.
We should start offering them for transplantation early next year,&quot; says Dr. Décary who describes this practice of cord blood sampling as very popular.
&quot;Many mothers are disappointed not to have access to it&quot;, as Héma-Québec does not have the necessary means to offer this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Québec.
