Charest points to the North
The prime minister does not rule out holding elections before the end of the year.
After the general council of the Liberal Party ended, Jean Charest went yesterday to Jean-Talon, in Québec where the new Minister of Health, Yves Bolduc, (on the left), is trying to be elected in today&#39;s partial elections.
&quot;Expanding the borders of our last great northern frontier&quot;: this is the long-term ambition of Jean Charest, presented yesterday in Levis, by means of tools with a strong visual impact, on the occasion of the general council of the Liberal Party of Quebec.
Behind him, during his speech, a sort of &quot;image mill&quot; is projected.
Spectacular negatives of hydroelectric dams, mineral crops, images of Quebec seen with &quot;Google Maps&quot;, maps, etc. were mixed up on three big screens.
Big means like in the middle of the electoral campaign.
Moreover, during the press conference, the prime minister refused to rule out the start of the autumn elections, although he noted that he was very busy.
The &quot;North Plan&quot; is the fourth point of a &quot;project&quot; that the prime minister says he has for Quebec, that of a &quot;new economic space&quot;, which includes a first agreement with France on manpower, a second agreement between Canada and Europe and other agreements with Ontario.
Often mentioned in the prime minister&#39;s most recent speeches, the opening of the North - the northern territory at the 49th parallel - had never before been the subject of a presentation.
However, the prime minister limited himself to explaining why the North would be &quot;a jewel with immense potential&quot;, but did not comment on timing or investment quotas, just as he did not explain what the precise priorities will be in the implementation of future projects .
At most, he limited himself to pointing out what in his opinion deserves a priority position: hydroelectricity, forests, but above all the mining sector, which following the growth of emerging countries and the reconstruction of public infrastructures has experienced various improvements .
According to Charest&#39;s list, the North contains &quot;nickel, zinc, copper, platinum, gold, silver, iron, titanium, and even diamonds.&quot;
That &quot;territory twice the size of France,&quot; is here, it&#39;s Quebec.
Not only is it here, but it is inherent in us&quot;, he insisted, as if to solicit a national founding myth.
The foundations of Quebec are rooted in its relationship with the North, he underlined : Gold Rush in Abitibi, national engineering, James Bay.
&quot;It&#39;s up to us, it&#39;s our future&quot;, he added, after a dramatic pause to contemplate the immense map behind him.
The North, 70% of the territory of Quebec, includes a part of Labrador that Quebec has always claimed, the prime minister specified during the press conference.
&quot;It is a position traditionally held by all governments.
There is a borderline on which there has been no agreement for a long time and when the opportunity arises, I will reiterate that position in the name of the government,&quot; he indicated.
After all, &quot;considering climate change, we need to reevaluate the North&quot;, he declared speaking of the North-West Passage, which will be open throughout the year due to the melting of the ice.
In this new geopolitical context, the prime minister believes that occupying the territory is a duty.&quot;
What about the locals, First Nations and Inuit?
The prime minister said that the Quebec government would be very attentive in this regard and that the project would meet their interests, especially those of young people.
Two ex-ministers from different parties, Pierre Corbeil and Michel Létourneau (ex-deputy of the PQ d&#39;Ungava), have already started the consultation of about thirty communities.
An interministerial committee chaired by Benoît Pelletier and in which Julie Boulet (Transport and Natural Resources) holds an important position, has begun work.
The prime minister does not rule out a major meeting, &quot;not necessarily a summit&quot;, but a moment in which &quot;common visions will be provided&quot;
Moreover, the development of the North would comply with the principles of sustainable development.
The Northern Plan will be &quot;concerted, orderly and will respect the environment&quot;, he promised.
Jean Charest described this &quot;project&quot; as a continuum with that of the Liberal prime ministers who preceded it.
&quot;Like the liberals who preceded us, we know how to distinguish ourselves by transforming challenges into new opportunities for growth and development.&quot;
This was also one of the recurring themes of the weekend, which began on Friday with a large cocktail party in honor of the 50th anniversary of Jean Lesage&#39;s arrival at the head of the party.
One of the resolutions adopted proposes renaming the Centrale Beauharnois into the Adélard-Godbout Dam.
&quot;From Godbout, creator of Hydro-Québec, to Lesage who nationalized hydroelectricity, to Bourassa, creator of James Bay, our party has always known how to shape the future,&quot; said Jean Charest.
During the press conference, he resorted to another reference, conservative this time, the &quot;Roads to the North&quot; program of John Diefenbaker, prime minister from 1957 to 1963.
Addressing the Eastmain1a-Ruper hydroelectric dam project, Charest specified that its commissioning would be scheduled for 2012.
&quot;All this remains between us, but I feel that we will make it&quot;, he confessed to his militants, arousing heartfelt applause.
Indeed, the prime minister, who in April said there would be no elections in 2008 and probably not even 2009, has not ruled out the possibility of launching a poll in the autumn, which could happen in accordance with the law.
He stresses that he is certainly very busy, especially in a federal council mission to China and in the Quebec-New York summit.
The weekend&#39;s General Council provided the Liberal frontrunner with a platform for nationalist resolutions, especially &quot;constitutional aspirations&quot; that passed like oil: the PLQ above all calls for the recognition of &quot;Quebec&#39;s specificity&quot; in the Constitution.
He also hopes that Quebec will nominate members of Canada&#39;s Broadcasting and Telecommunications Council and that they will have a veto over decisions made in Quebec.
As far as the opposition is concerned, the draft of the Northern Plan has been met with skepticism.
The leader of the PQ, Pauline Marois, dusted off the Northern Quebec Development Policy launched by the Landry government in 2001.
According to her, the liberal government, which came to power in 2003, would not have complied with its application.
If he had done so,&quot; we would have progressed today&quot; commented Marois alongside the candidate of the Jean-Talon (election took place today), Françoise Mercure.
The ADQ has stated that it supports the government&#39;s adoption of the Northern Plan.
&quot;What we hope is that all this is not simply perceived as a show&quot;, commented the leader Sébastien Proulx, Mario Dumont&#39;s replacement, who just returned from vacation today.
Letters - A country dishonored
It was Vic Toews, former &quot;Justice&quot; minister (ironically) in the Harper cabinet, who allowed himself to declare last summer that Louise Arbor was a &quot;shame&quot; to Canada.
Disgracing in this way a woman who fought relentlessly for justice and who deserves our full admiration says a lot about both the prime minister&#39;s entourage and Stephen Harper himself.
Here we are before a government which is the only one of all the Western countries involved in not having repatriated one of its citizens detained in the Guantanamo concentration camp.
A government that does not take into account the fact that Omar Khadr was a mere teenager at the time the events accused of him took place.
The only government which, despite having signed the Geneva Convention, reneges on its word and lets a child soldier rot in inhumane conditions.
The only one who trusts in a travesty of justice to establish the guilt of the accused.
We recall, by way of information, that UNICEF, Amnesty International and the Canadian Bar Association, in particular, are calling for the repatriation of Omar Khadra so that he can be subjected to a regular trial in Canada.
It is precisely that same government that closes its eyes to torture: it matters very little that a young adult is now psychologically destroyed, perhaps forever, after so many years of abuse.
We don&#39;t realize it yet, but we are witnessing an insidious erosion of our rights, freedom and &quot;democracy&quot;, a word that Harper never ceases to flaunt and that sounds so senseless on his lips.
Here we have arrived at the moment in which there is no longer any morality: a Canadian citizen can be ill-treated, tortured, arbitrarily imprisoned according to the discretion of a until now minority head of government (to see what will happen after October 14th…).
Many voters believe that a party that preaches Virtue, Respect for Law and Order represents salvation: they do not see that this government has renounced what constituted the reputation and dignity of our country.
Herein lies the shame, Mr. Toews, in the renunciation of all this, and nowhere else.
Free Opinion - Barrick Gold&#39;s Orwellian Speech
In its Sept. 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from M. Patrick J. Garver, managing vice president of Canadian mining firm Barrick Gold.
Pursuing an Orwellian logic, the latter claims that the largest gold company in the world has filed a six million libel suit against three authors and a small penniless publishing house with the intention of starting a &quot;transparent public debate&quot;.
While it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth they judge, especially in the case of a libel suit, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this major difference is completely hidden by Garver.
Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to bring to ruin anyone who dares to take a position contrary to its.
No matter the outcome of the trial, the writers and the publisher of the book Black Canada will have to spend a large sum of money in order to organize their defense and fight, with decidedly unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers financed from the pockets practically without mining company fund.
After all, in these unequal battles, the tactic is often to ruin the defendant in order to impose a consensual regulation that gags the opposition as well as frighten anyone who dares to pronounce themselves again on the matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it would have had to present its view of the facts before the public.
Contrary to what happens in many countries where Barrick Gold works, in Canada debates usually take place with the exchange of views and not with a truncheon.
It would therefore have been sufficient for the company to open its books, its documents, and establish a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications and the funding of teams of independent researchers who could have shed light on the matter.
But Barrick Gold doesn&#39;t seem to have too much faith in public opinion and rudely rejects the petitions and letters in support of the authors of Black Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can ask for a &quot;public&quot; debate when his contempt for that same audience is so evident?
In the vice-president&#39;s world, it seems that this word refers exclusively to highly paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; here is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democratic system, even denigrators have the right to speak.
What Barrack Gold doesn&#39;t understand – or doesn&#39;t want to understand – is that the public who support the authors and editors of Black Canada do so primarily because they reject the mining company&#39;s brutal means.
This public is ready to listen to Barrick and to judge, but on the basis of civil exchanges of opinion, and not in the light of what many perceive as a sort of gag (researching the &quot;public debate&quot;, Barrick Gold has just given to the authors of Black Canada an ultimatum ordering them to stop using that word…)
Beyond Garver&#39;s surreal speech, the lawsuit filed by Barrack Gold constitutes a direct attack on the freedom of university research and the pursuit of truth, indispensable in any democratic society.
It denies the right to cite authentic sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which represent the very basis of intellectual work.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to study and discuss topics that are inconvenient for the richest companies in the world, on pain of multiple lawsuits, who will be able to do it?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so by following scientific norms as the authors of Black Canada do.
You have the right to reply.
For a long time, the university environment, of which we belong, has been able to manage debates and disagreements and to resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold&#39;s excessive measures clearly show that, contrary to its claims, it does not seek transparent debate at all.
This is to the detriment of the university world, as is the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to adopt measures capable of limiting abusive lawsuits.
Operation - Rescue for Wall Street - Dialogue between Republicans and Democrats
The Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, representatives of the Republican and Democratic camps, yesterday finally reached an agreement on the largest bailout plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the 700 billion US dollar plan, which aims to put a stop to the financial crisis that has been weighing on Wall Street for months, has yet to be ratified by both houses of Congress.
In particular, it provides for: checks on its effective implementation by elected leaders, new mechanisms that guarantee the repayment of public money, new provisions to limit the number of houses foreclosed for non-payments, as well as a right to inspect wages paid to managers of protected companies.
US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi and Republican negotiating table Senator Judd Gregg announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday at the end of a marathon of negotiations that lasted two days.
&quot;We have made great progress toward an effective market deal,&quot; said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
&quot;Every decision has been made in such a way as to safeguard the economy and the American people from the crisis currently underway on Wall Street.&quot;, explained the Democrat.
&quot;It is the crucial point: if we had not acted in this way, priceless heartache and turmoil would have poured into the daily lives of Americans,&quot; said Republican Judd Gregg.
The conclusion of the negotiations was marked by concerns regarding the impact of a new bankruptcy on investors.
The time limit agreed corresponded to the opening of the markets this morning.
Joining the negotiation later, the two candidates for the American presidential elections showed themselves rather in favor of the agreement, without however avoiding expressing their dissatisfaction with the adoption of extreme solutions.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama deserves credit for having added some provisions to the agreement, in particular the one that will allow owners to maintain their domicile and the one relating to the salaries for executives of companies covered by the State.
&quot;When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of others, there is nothing to be happy about.
But these measures are necessary,&quot; he commented on the American TV screen.
Interviewed on another channel to find out if he will vote in favor of the plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied: &quot;I would like to analyze the details, but I hope so.&quot;
&quot;According to what I&#39;ve read, it&#39;s something that we all have to digest and that will allow us to move forward&quot;
The option of no intervention is simply unacceptable,&quot; he said.
The 700 billion plan aims to buy back the doubtful loans, risky and unsaleable assets of American financial institutions with taxpayers&#39; money.
The plan comes after 14 months of crisis due to the bursting of a real estate bubble which first of all led to the collapse of risky mortgage loans (mortgages), to then extend to other more widespread forms of credit instruments (PCAA) and lead to the freezing of the liquidity and disarray of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of incumbent Republicans who scuppered the first draft of a deal last week.
It seems to have come out of that impasse since the Democrats have accepted that the &quot;toxic&quot; assets of some troubled companies are only protected by the government, rather than bought.
In order to accommodate everyone, a provision was added in Congress that if the government were to face losses over the next five years from such a program, it could impose new taxes in order to keep your balance.
The new plan provides for the payment of an initial sum of 250 billion to which another 100 billion can be added if the president deems it necessary.
The payment of 350 billion should be ratified by a further vote in Congress.
In exchange for his help, Washington will get stakes in protected companies that will be worth dividends in the event of a profit and which he can sell when the dust settles.
Under the plan, the federal government will have the ability to delay foreclosure proceedings on home loans and to set limits on the salary and severance pay paid to executives of the affected firms.
Starting today, the architects of the plan would like to submit it to a vote in the House of Representatives, and to a vote in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all efforts, it is still not certain that their plan will be given the green light.
In fact, yesterday there were several votes against the project, both in the Republican and Democratic camps.
&quot;Evidently, Washington doesn&#39;t hear you,&quot; Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, told his constituents.
&quot;Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But certainly not take advantage of the taxpayers..
Leading a small group in Congress dubbed the &quot;skeptics&#39; caucus,&quot; Democratic Rep. Brad Sherman presents the situation differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
&quot;Four hundred eminent professors of economics, including three Nobel Prize winners, have written to say: we ask Congress not to jump to hasty conclusions and carefully examine the way forward,&quot; he declared yesterday.
At the same time, in Europe, there was once again proof of the global nature of the crisis.
After an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros ($16.3 billion).
Intervention by the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary when French bank BNS Paribas said it would pull out of buying its bankrupt competitor after losing 2 billion euros ($2.9 billion) for the risky home loan crisis in the United States.
Fortis has 85,000 employees and is one of Europe&#39;s twenty largest banks and ten largest insurers.
&quot;It&#39;s not money lost,&quot; Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
In return, influence and the right to vote in banking matters are levied.
It&#39;s certainly something savers and families appreciate now that times are shaky.&quot;
During this period, at the other end of the Channel, the British government appears to be on its way to nationalizing another bank teetering on the edge of the financial crisis.
According to the British press, the government would take over all the loans currently outstanding at the Bradford and Bringley bank, including more than 41 billion (75.5 billion dollars) of real estate loans.
Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it will buy the British bank&#39;s branches and customer accounts.
Since the beginning of the economic crisis, Bradford and Bringley will be the second bank, after Northern Rock, to undergo a process of nationalization by the British government.
Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death of a committed icon
The blue-eyed beauty was for a long time his trump card, for others his weak point.
Had the American actor with the bewitching smile freed himself from the narcissistic mirror?
Yes and no.
His discretion, sensitivity and obvious talent would have expelled him from that circle of powerful consecrated to real sacred monsters.
But what constancy!
Paul Newman, who died on Friday at the age of 83 on his Connecticut ranch following lung cancer, remains one of the last icons of American cinema of the glories.
Less monumental than Brando, whom he resembled and of whom he was for a long time a sort of rival on the screen, more prudent in his game, certainly more fragile, but he too spokesperson for freedom and the development of dramatic convictions.
From mixed couples magical children are often born.
He was born in Ohio in 1925, to a German Jewish father and a Hungarian mother.
From these European roots will be born one of the glorious faces of the American dream.
A humble ego, ultimate seal of quality.
Since a whole country was recognized in him in love with the safe made man, the fighter of the Pacific war, proud in combat, who in the early 50s studied dramatic art at Yale, subsequently attended the Actors Studio in New York, before triumph in the theatre, on television and soon in the cinema.
That same civil rights activist was also the racing driver who finished second at the 24 Hours of Mans in 1979, as well as a sex symbol, albeit part of a model couple since 1958 with actress Joanne Woodward.
The gray areas of a reserved, discreet, committed star, allergic to show-business scandals, leave with him, the mystery of which will never be completely revealed.
An honest man, in the noblest sense of the term.
The passing of Paul Newman was heartbreaking for cinephiles this weekend, as his great characters populate the black screen of memories.
Over half a century of American cinema in full transformation is proposed through his interpretations.
The charming cowboy of Butch Cassidy (1969) and that boy incapable of desiring a fiery wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in Cat on a Hot Tin Roof adapted by Tennessee Williams in 1958 are confused in memory.
More recently, we remember him as the sensitive Mr. Bridge (1990), troubled by a marriage that did not deliver on its promises.
Many other Paul Newmans have gone down in history.
The boxer Rocky Graziano, delinquent, tormented, violent, unforgettable in Someone Up There Loves Me, by Robert Wise, a role intended for James Dean and reprized after his death, which officially launched Newman in 1956.
That nice criminal in the excellent Sting, Oscar for best film in 1973.
Bitter and vengeful billiard player in Lo Spaccone, a magnificent film by Robert Rossen (1961), The Color of Money by Martin Scorsese, which in 1987 earned him the only Oscar out of 9 nominations.
That face through the years was hers.
Him again.
Epochs follow one another along its path.
Young people know him above all for the cult movie Slap Shot by George Roy Hill (1977), in the role of Reggie Dunlop, coach of an unorthodox ice hockey team.
His fans found him again in 1994 in Mr. Hula Hoop, by the Coen brothers.
The circle had come full circle with one last role as godfather of the Irish mob in Road to Perdition in 2003.
Unlike the bigger film legends who soon left the craft, Newman would hang out in theaters for a long time, denouncing Hollywood in all its glitz, parties and concessions.
Bertrand Tavernier, French cinematographer, defined it, with a touch of irony, &quot;a living challenge to underplaying&quot;, judging its performances exaggerated.
The profession hasn&#39;t always been a game for handsome Paul Newman, to whom roles seemed to fall like godsend.
However, he often preferred the role of the outcast to that of the young actor: neurotic characters, scoundrels or desperate alcoholics, of which he expressed disarray and rebellion with his perfect features.
As a director, Newman revealed unknown shades of his real demure sensibility.
Jennifer&#39;s First Time, 1968 (based on Canadian Margaret Laurence&#39;s novel), starring his wife Joanne Woodward in the title role, painted a subtle feminine portrait of melancholy.
He, who lost his son Scott to an overdose, dedicated the film Harry and Son to him in 1984, a discreet and sad film.
Among the countless tributes showered on Newman yesterday, his great friend and old comrade in arms Robert Redford (they had acted together in The Sting and Butch Cassidy) said with infinite sadness &quot;His presence has made my life and this country better&quot; .
Generosity and love of life, two great characteristics of the late actor.
Beyond a legendary career, a great militant for civil rights, ecology, independent cinema, a protester of the Hollywood drift, dies.
We will have seen his face stand out on bottles of vinegar, sauces, biscuits and other foods, judging it as a choice in bad taste, even if it was born as a gag.
The proceeds from those sales were, however, going to his Foundation for Troubled Children.
Newman, instead of resting on his myth, chose to commit himself to the end.
He left his five daughters a letter saying &quot;Always and to the end, your father was incredibly grateful to his lucky stars.&quot;
It was a privilege to be there.&quot;
And it was an equal privilege for us to follow the path of such a clear and generous American artist.
Model citizen, therefore, and much more.
What was produced in the invoice factory of Zuschlag &amp; Co.?
Soon, on October 8, the hearing of the criminal case against János Zuschlag and associates will be discussed.
The politician and his associates are accused of repeated commercial fraud committed as part of a criminal association that caused considerable damage, and of other crimes, including forgery of documents.
According to the Prosecutor&#39;s Office, the money obtained from calls for tenders was used by them for private purposes, and they often certified that the activities were carried out through false invoices.
The state and municipal money, totaling 65 million guilders, ended up partly in the coffers of the Fiatal Baloldal organization, partly in the pockets of some people.
According to the method, disclosed by the investigating authorities, they withdrew the money obtained from calls for tenders on the basis of invoices for non-existent operations and the associations never fulfilled their obligations.
According to the indictment, most of the invoices were false.
To make them, the invoice blocks were purchased at the Józsefváros market, the circular stamps instead were manufactured in Kiskunhalas.
And to decide on behalf of which companies to issue the invoices, was established among other things during the trip to the hills above Balaton where János Zuschlag had sent István Lados.
According to the latter&#39;s confession, he had to choose boarding houses and restaurants.
He requested an invoice for drinks, and invoices were then prepared based on these to be forwarded to the calls for tenders, among others, to those of the Ministry of Youth and Sport, the Ministry of Labor and Social Affairs and the Municipality of Budapest.
Most of these are the work of István Lados and András Őri who, according to our information, mainly drafted the reports needed to obtain funding.
One of the choices of the &quot;study trip&quot; of Lados was a brewery.
According to two invoices issued by Zuschlag and partners in 2003, the restaurant place provided meals for a group of 90 people from the Biztos Pont Egyesület Association.
However, according to the restaurateur, so many people would not enter the restaurant all together.
Similarly, the invoice issued in the summer of 2002 to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, later called Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, is full of formal and content errors.
A boarding house in Badacsonytomaj has only three rooms, more than 10 people could not stay overnight, yet the invoice included 130 guests.
But the imaginative invoice compilers exaggerated when they reported Pigal Kft., which also deals with catering, whose accounts - according to information released to the judicial authorities - did not even include documents in the name of the companies Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá .
Győző Farkas, director of the company, told hvg.hu that when he was summoned to the prosecutor&#39;s office and they showed him the invoices, he immediately understood that they were fake documents.
&quot;On the stamp, the name and VAT number of our company were in the wrong place.&quot;
He added: in addition to the formal reasons, the fact that according to the invoice, one hundred people were accommodated, when in total they have eleven rooms and there are not so many beds, did not add up.
In addition, the invoice was for catering and their restaurant has not been in operation for some time.
The assiduous invoice compilers did not bother to inform themselves that the Budapest travel agency of their choice only organizes trips abroad, so they foolishly indicated on the invoice with cash payment trips to Hungary, which did not agree with the practice of issuing company invoices.
In addition, as demonstrated during the investigation, VAT was also included on the invoice, while travel to countries outside the European Union is VAT exempt.
Among other things, the amount of VAT was also incorrect on the four documents issued by the Hotel Révfülöp Kft. in favor of the Jobb Jövőért foundation, in fact on the services offered by the company VAT must be applied at 15% and not at 25% as indicated on the invoices, moreover, the hotel employees issued only printed invoices, while the fabricated invoice was written by hand.
In addition to this, the &quot;issuers&quot; have ruined other invoices, in the case of a company they have indicated the transport of goods by road as the activity carried out, as we learn from the Prosecutor&#39;s proceeding, an activity that was not carried out by the company originally founded for consultancy of investments.
Furthermore, due to formal defects - due to non-compliant invoice format, false stamp - it was discovered that the invoices issued in favor of Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, of XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont are false.
The same happened in the case of Ravenna Bt. or Kunfehértó Sports Field, whose representatives denied having issued the invoices in question.
The forgers also paid no attention to the fact that HIB Kft. of Nyíregyháza was in liquidation when (2001) a group of Fiatal Városért Egyesület lunched there, precisely for this reason the company&#39;s liquidator, according to our information, denied that he issued that invoice.
They billed knowingly
Another group of invoice issuers are those who were aware that they had to issue fictitious invoices.
The Esély Budapestért Alapítvány foundation issued an invoice at the request of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták in favor of the Együtt foundation to Harmadik Évezredért of almost 4 million guilders.
Ludovic Györfi, one of the defendants, according to the indictment, persuaded the director of Collab Kft. to issue fictitious invoices.
Biogate Kft, currently in liquidation, also collaborated with Zuschlag and partners, which in 2003 supplied issued invoices worth around 5 million guilders to the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány foundation, the Atlasz Egyesület association and the Vörösfenyő Egyesület association, behind which there was no real economic activity.
Not even movement of money because the invoices prepared were then reversed, but the associations forgot to include this aspect in their documents.
The following group of invoicing companies includes those who can be connected with the defendants.
e.g. Ivan Kubatov, authorized to the address of the general manager of Delta Trió Kft, based in Budapest but not available there, which is involved in the trading of fuel and motor vehicles.
The company issued various invoices in October, November and December 2005 relating to the sale of IT equipment, for a value of approximately 18 million guilders.
According to the investigation data, Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas, under liquidation since 14 September 2005, bought these invoices.
The general director of this company was a Romanian to whom Ivan Kubatov allegedly forwarded documents relating to the company between 2002 and 2005.
As far as we know, Kubatov acknowledged during the investigation that he had issued invoices in the name of the company to the firms Atlasz, Hoppá and in Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány and the equivalent value was taken from him.
At the express request of Ivan Kubatov Romanian masons founded the companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt.
