The Psychology of Overbidding: Why Spend More Money?
At auctions buyers are inclined to spend more, to overvalue the goods.
Neurologists and economists researchers at the University of New York have managed to discover the neuro-economic basis of this well-known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, men don&#39;t want to fall behind in a competition such as the eBay auction, so they are willing to pay a higher price.
Research has sought to trace the nervous pattern of this &quot;match&quot; at the level of the nervous system using experimental rods.
One group of volunteers played the lotto, the other group of players participated in an auction while they examined the active areas of the brain of the people participating in the experiment with the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method.
In both games the participants could win money, but in the auction game, in which the substantial element is to bid more than the other, the striatum under the cerebral cortex comes into intensive function when one loses the game.
This area of the brain, in addition to other functions, plays a role in the &quot;self-gratification&quot; mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the price increase is explained by the avoidance of the vehement reaction of the striatum.
To back up their theory, the research team economists conducted a financial tracking survey.
In this investigation, three groups bid against a partner under different conditions.
The control group was told what the real value of the product in question was and they placed their bets.
In addition to this, another group has promised that if they win, they will receive another prize of 15 dollars.
The third group would receive $15 before the auction, but group members would lose their money if they lost at the auction.
The difference between the two groups consisted in the fact that for one of them the gain was underlined, while for the other the loss.
Proving the neurologists&#39; hypothesis, members of the group playing &quot;against the loss&quot; were willing to make higher bets than the control or &quot;winning&quot; group.
&quot;These results are not deducible from any of the previously existing economic theories.
In fact, up to now these explained the phenomena that can be found at auctions with the joy of winning and with the avoidance of risk.
Only neurological imaging methods helped to resolve the contradiction between the two theories, so that we came to a third explanation&quot; - said Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economics of New York University.
Hepatitis: when to see a doctor?
Nearly half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary chronic liver disease is cited as the leading cause of death.
In Hungary, the number of hepatitis patients amounts to one hundred thousand, of which only 7,000 are treated: the reason is that many patients do not know they are infected.
The definition hepatitis is the collective name for contagious liver diseases caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between the symptoms, typical are hepatitis and jaundice, but their pathogens and the diseases caused differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses are spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E via the alimentary canal (e.g. water and infected food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body fluids (semen, vaginal discharge, saliva).
For those who travel it is useful to get vaccinated against viruses A and B, there is no vaccine against virus C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consuming infected food, accompanied by general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
Then yellowish spots form on the skin and on the whites of the eyes, the stools become light and the urine dark, healing takes place within two to three weeks.
One million people die each year worldwide from hepatitis B, the most severe form of the disease, which causes liver tumors and cirrhosis of the liver.
The main reason is, according to estimates, only one in ten people receive drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if left untreated it can cause cirrhosis of the liver and liver tumors.
Most infected people do not know they have contracted the disease because the pathogens subtly destroy liver cells, in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
So prevention and regular medical tests are very important.
This disease is much more frequent than the average in three groups: those who have had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts and tattooed people.
In the world today the number of people infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus amounts to 200 million.
Since even a routine laboratory examination reveals the disease, it is worthwhile to consult the family doctor when you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
Recognized in time, the disease is curable, the virus can be eliminated from the body, thus the infective power ceases and the formation of tumors can be prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, organized for the first time in 2004 by patient organizations worldwide.
The purpose is to draw attention to chronic viral hepatitis, the causes of its development and early recognition of the disease.
