Who believes in God feels less pain?
According to the result of a recent survey, religious faith works as a kind of analgesic that has made the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
Scientists at the University of Oxford have performed an interesting experiment examining how belief in god affects the sensation of pain, reported the British Telegraph.
As part of the rather bizarre investigation, 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists were electroshocked, while all of them looked at a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to fend off much of the pain.
Thanks to the exploratory technique of the human brain it was discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of the brain responsible for pain control.
The test is the first of a series of researches in which not only academics but also scientists, philosophers and theologians from the University are taking part.
The test took place exactly like this: an instrument that emits discharges and passes electroshock was connected to the left hand of the experiment subject.
The researchers asked participants to focus on two paintings, the Virgin Mary painted in the 17th century by Sassoferrato and the Lady with an Ermine by Leonardo da Vinci painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the review hoped that the image of the Virgin Mary would give rise to a sort of religious state among believers, while Leonardo&#39;s painting was chosen because it didn&#39;t differ too much from the other and they considered it to have a reassuring effect.
The subjects of the experiment spent half an hour in front of the MRI scanner and during this time they received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive series, while looking at either the religious-themed painting or the other.
Catholics reported that seeing the Virgin Mary made them feel &quot;safe&quot;, as if &quot;someone was taking care&quot; of them and &quot;they were soothed and filled with peace&quot;.
Looking at the religious-themed image, they accounted for 12% less pain than when they had Leonardo&#39;s work in front of them.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who took part in the test himself, believes that such a result can be achieved with any image with a strong effect even for atheists, but one must find the right image.
“We need to look for an image towards which they have very positive feelings, like a mother or father,” said the psychologist.
Anglican bishop Tom Wright welcomed the result of the research.
&quot;The practice of faith is supposed to change, and in many cases it does change our personalities.&quot; - added Wright.
After the excellent results the only question remains if a painting of a Madonna by Leonardo or another painter of similar caliber is presented to believers, what effect could that have on pain control?
Would the vision of a quality Virgin Mary bring better results?
You are what you say about yourself
On its 10th birthday, Google can claim to be as much in people&#39;s pockets as it is in the sky above their heads; he knows where they spent their holidays, which clinic they attend and what interests them.
However, according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company&#39;s directors, this is still not enough.
Instead, what concerns the skeptics who make a comparison with the Orwellian nightmare, they don&#39;t really see the substance of web 2.0.
Recently Eric Schmidt told the Financial Times that the main purpose of Google is to collect as much personal data of its users and this is necessary to comply with the original goal of the founders of Google which was: &quot;we put all the information of the world!&quot;.
According to the director of Google interviewed the company, after 10 years of revolutionary work, it is still at the beginning of being able to manage all information.
When asked what will happen in five years, Schmidt replied: he would like it if Google could answer questions like &quot;what am I doing tomorrow?&quot; or &quot;what would be the right job for me?&quot; but software can&#39;t answer seemingly simple questions because they don&#39;t know enough about users.
Not all Internet users are aware that exactly the searched words are recorded during their internet searches, from which IP address they are searched and on which page the interested parties stop after the search.
Through the Personalized Search launched two years ago, users eg. they can store their browsing history, they can look back at what they searched for and clicked on, which will generate much better tailored results in the long run; Recommendations are based on this same logic with which the system offers us products and services based on our previously declared and recorded preferences.
