In most cases, the counter-reactions of internet users are caused by the fear felt by the size of the potential power represented by the company, and not by the sense of guilt, fear of punishment, desire for freedom or even rebellion against power .
However, one fact is confirmed and that is that all the searched expressions are not only recorded but in justified cases they can also be provided to third parties, in such legal cases nothing defends the personal rights of Internet users.
Perhaps the most striking example of this in recent times was the coordinated action against pedophiles in Brazil, in which Google forwarded information to the Brazilian government that made it possible to identify pedophiles from the Google-maintained Orkut community page .
However, Internet users concerned about personal rights sighed with relief in May when the company - in agreement with the electronic legal protection association EFF - successfully proved the truth in court against the FBI: even later it cannot force Google under no statute of incorporation to provide any information secretly requested by the FBI.
(At the same time, the federal government successfully snatched nearly 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search phrases obtained in connection with the confirmation of the child protection law passed years earlier, but still failed to obtain search lists of individual users and the &#39;entire list of web pages and keywords dating back two months.)
Google&#39;s judgment is therefore rather contradictory: those who are afraid to provide their personal data lash out at Google because they believe that in this way their intimate sphere and private life is affected by starting to use its services and they rise up with the rebellion due to the multinationals that stand out for the conservative image.
Meanwhile, American geek culture and the proliferation of computer enthusiasts, activists and users who have appeared in many countries see them as the future generation of big companies, the &quot;cool corporation&quot;, as opposed to their rival, Microsoft, dismissed as the conqueror of the world. because of Windows, even though they both fight for the same goal.
This can happen because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask its users for an identification code, does not ask for money for its services, the source code is always kept up to date and the program package is much more accessible, youthful and cool than the official practice of the software giant.
But it can also happen because geeks see exactly the problematic relationship between personal rights and the internet, which precisely implies one of the most often repeated keywords in recent years, web 2.0.
Web 2.0 speaks of nothing but collaboration, of intentionally leaving traces behind us and exploiting the communication channels at our disposal and while the dimension of these changes for each individual, the substance is the same: showing ourselves.
An average young person can create profiles on multiple community pages, from Facebook to Xanga, they can link them with other services such as Twitter or last.fm which lists their musical tastes, all of these can be entered into systems such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm , he can also write blogs on which his most recent photo galleries stored on Flickr or Picasa automatically appear.
Meanwhile, we read of numerous exemplary cases from which it is clear that the girl, seeing the series of photos taken in the morning by the common circle of friends, easily learns who her perfidious boyfriend spent the night with or a company can fire one of its employees because he wrote an honest opinion on the top management: one thing is sure, the concept of private life has now completely reconsidered.
Those who live a life online manage to show themselves and so we can formulate the fundamental thesis behind the behavior of young people.
Those who want to hide something or just want to avoid the monopoly of Google can do it (starting for example with Scroogle using the Google search system but at the same time voluntarily leaving no traces).
Not a few people who purposely don&#39;t register on community pages to avoid being found, Google&#39;s online applications, from word processing to image management and news gathering, can be replaced with alternative versions not linked to huge server parks and which do not make up our best profile to date.
Public opinion is not even waiting in secret for the moment when Google will pull out its claws.
Currently the company with its $156 billion value is worth more than IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion) or Coca Cola ($110 billion), AdWords/AdSense advertising spaces threaten the revenues of advertising agencies, the services introduced in record time instead cause great discomfort not only to Microsoft but also to numerous software development companies.
However, critical observers find some alarming points alongside all of this: for example, the top management of the company completely rejected the protests of the employees after doubling the company kindergarten fee, considered the repeated daily catering of the employees to be too expensive, all of this however, it discounts the fact that in 2006 Google bowed its head to the Chinese government and under their agreement the company will filter out all results that offend good taste and the interests of the Chinese regime.
An internal rule of the company seems to be not to advertise a new service in advance but only when it will be usable, one thing is sure, however, that the foreseeable problems of the coming months and years will move the world in one point: while some believe that the scanning and archiving of Google books and magazines will assume such proportions that the company will soon find itself in front of the American Supreme Court, others are afraid of the Health system, in fact in this we can create our own health profile with our reports, doctors and problems .
The fact that Google is building a genetic database may offer good material for the next generation of science fiction writers, the famous Cory Doctorow&#39;s story Scroogled describes the future with Orwellian accents, in which a man with Google data can be approached in alarming way.
