The intelligent machine imitates the flight of the bumblebee
What could be a better way to develop collision avoidance technologies than to mimic obstacle sensors found in nature?
For example those of bees.
In the astonishing project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the hornets gave Nissan engineers an initial strategic cue on how to build the next generation of collision avoidance systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the biomimetic robot BR23C, a robotic mini-car with the properties of bees, with the ultimate aim of creating a system capable of avoiding all collisions.
Flying bees form their own oval personal space that really looks a lot like our protective shield - explained Kazuhiro Doi, director of PR technologies and research and development at the exhibition.
Important is the role of the bee&#39;s eyesight, capable of a view of 300 degrees in any direction.
Engineers drew on the telemetry laser idea to copy the bee&#39;s vision function.
The BR23C detects obstacles up to two meters away within a 180 degree radius, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor which immediately transforms it into a command to avoid a collision.
In a fraction of a second the robot perceives the obstacle and then, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes direction by turning the wheels by the amount necessary to avoid the accident.
This avoidance maneuver, differently from the current system, takes place in a completely instinctive way.
&quot;If this were not the case, the robot car would not be able to react quickly to avoid collisions&quot; - explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and of the robot car project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the damageable and innermost layer of the protective shield, within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must mirror what one bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must take place in the blink of an eye.
But unlike bees the deflection cannot go up or down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and in the direction of steerability of the wheels.
In this way instead of the infinite possibilities available to the bees to avoid the other bees, the robot, as available possibility, can rotate on itself, accelerate and slow down.
The BR23C is powered by Li-Polymer batteries, which are lighter and have a higher energy density, which means they last longer than Li-ion batteries.
According to Andoh, the instantaneousness of the intelligent reaction is important, not the processing of data or even less the ability to store them.
This robot has to process some input in seconds and react.
There is no need to memorize them and react with intuitive logic based on previous maneuver data, thus using only a few tens of Kb of memory.
No need for gigabyte or megabyte memory.
This is the first step in the development of instantaneous collision avoidance technology which Nissan expects to be installed in production vehicles within 10 years.
A further application possibility can be represented by the unification with the GPS satellite navigation system which leads to the destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
