The fox in the chicken coop
In America, life and health insurers, based on people&#39;s drug purchase data, often refuse to take out an insurance contract.
Privacy experts fear the market for data is spiraling out of control.
“There is a privacy program that the use of drug prescription data depends on the approval of the individual concerned in any case.
This program must be in independent hands, otherwise it is like entrusting the chicken coop to the fox&quot; - writes the Washington Post quoting Richard Dick, author of the program to follow the prescriptions of medicines.
Insurance companies subordinate the insurance rate and the amount due in the event of accidents to the state of health of any customer and if they deem the risk too high, they do not stipulate the insurance.
Some time ago the customer had to undergo a medical examination and the contract was stipulated only after the outcome of the examination.
10 years ago, Dick invented a much cheaper procedure: based on the customer&#39;s identification code, it is possible to easily obtain information from pharmacies on which medicines he has purchased in the last year and a half and from this the program deduces which diseases he suffers from and in which health condition is found.
e.g. If you regularly buy large quantities of cholesterol reducers this means that your blood fat level is practically incurably high and is placed in the highest risk category.
There are various versions of the program on the market, some also determine the risk multiplier, so the insurer does not have much left over from the paper work, even if there are small difficulties.
Among the cons is that some medicines can be used for multiple purposes, e.g. some compounds can be used against migraine or hot flashes, but they are also effective against depression.
The latter, from an insurance-commercial point of view, is a factor of increased risk, the first two are not.
Separate companies have been formed for the request and processing of data and these, before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies, ask for the patient&#39;s approval.
Now the authorities are forcing them to do so even though they have so far not imposed fines for negligence.
Recently, some companies also process the results of laboratory tests and link them to medicine consumption data in order to provide a more precise picture of the patients&#39; state of health.
More and more companies have access to data and at the same time controlling usage will become increasingly difficult.
There is a separate law on privacy but its validity only extends to health services and insurance.
Before Congress there is a bill that gives the authorities the power to oversee companies specializing in data services.
Richard Dick admits that this is not enough: for this reason he has developed a program that links data forwarding with the approval expressed by the person concerned.
Another issue is that the person concerned can not so much withhold approval because otherwise the insurers will not enter into the contract.
So then in the end the hens are entrusted to the clemency of the fox.
