Listening to loud music for an extended period of time using portable music devices such as MP3 players can cause permanent hearing damage.
This is what the European Commission reports, which in a statement released in Brussels cites the opinion of the EU&#39;s Scientific Committee on Emerging and Recently Identified Health Risks (CSSERI), published today.
&quot;From this scientific opinion - reads the note - it emerges that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music with portable music devices weekly for more than one hour a day keeping the device at high volumes risk permanent hearing loss&quot;.
&quot;I am concerned that so many young people who frequently use portable music devices and mobile phones at high sound levels may unconsciously damage their hearing beyond repair,&quot; says Meglena Kuneva.
&quot;From the scientific findings - continues the EU manager - a clear risk emerges and we must react quickly.
Most importantly, we need to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
We also need to review existing control systems, in the light of this scientific advice, to ensure that they are fully effective and keep pace with new technology.&quot;
Brussels had asked the independent scientific committee to examine the problem, given the great use of portable musical devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise they originate.
&quot;Scientists - concludes the EU executive - confirm that there is cause for concern and the European Commission will now examine together with the Member States and stakeholders what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise coming from portable music devices and similar equipment&quot;.
Currently, there is already a European safety standard limiting the noise level of portable music equipment to 100 dB, but concerns are growing about hearing damage that can result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to greatly limit these damages by resorting to solutions such as reducing the levels and duration of exposure to noise.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee points out that users of portable music equipment, if they listen to music at high volumes (more than 89 decibels) for only 5 hours a week, exceed the limits currently in force relating to the maximum noise allowed in the workplace .
Those who listen to music in such conditions for longer periods risk permanent hearing loss after 5 years.
This would affect 5-10% of users of such devices and their number can be quantified between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
