The elites in danger
The phenomenon had already manifested itself a few days ago with the vote in the House of Representatives against the 700 billion dollar bailout plan launched by the White House: a significant portion of Americans was, and is, more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the economy.
Yesterday&#39;s New York Times confirms this by informing us that the current crisis is splitting the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old East Coast soul, moderate, in favor of federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul on the other hand, conservative, hostile to &quot;those from Washington&quot; and to the world of finance, especially strong in the Central and Southern states.
The soul, to be precise, which overwhelmingly made itself alive with the vow I mentioned at the beginning.
However, this just mentioned is only an example of the changes, of the great changes, which the current economic earthquake perhaps heralds or already lets us see: not only in the United States but throughout the West and perhaps not only here.
Both in the US and in Europe, the crisis seems to be working as an accelerator of phenomena that have been incubating for some time and which solidify and finally come to light in the new climate.
The first of these phenomena is the re-enactment, the extraordinary re-launching of the dual category State-sovereignty in relation to a sort of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is the crisis of banking-financial institutions which have, yes, close ties with foreign countries, but which above all see the budgets of people and families living in a single country, in a single State.
Which immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: namely how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those people and families who, among other things, are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically worldwide but politically it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems substantially out of the game or doesn&#39;t have much to say: the clear proof is given by the European Union which, divided as usual between the different interests and between the different state strategies, is unable to decide on any common political line.
And so it is from the government of every single State that everyone expects interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all the disbursement of funds: since when it gets cornered it is only the States that have the economic resources, the mass of financial resources capable of trying to put things back on track.
And they also possess the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of immeasurable value, in certain circumstances, which probably no market and no international organization will ever be able to dispose of to an analogous extent.
This new emphasis that the crisis places on the national-state element is moreover in perfect harmony with the ever greater importance that the most recent developments in the economy tend to attribute to a factor very closely connected to that element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had now entered the realm of the web, of ever more sophisticated technology, of the immaterial, while we were convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we suddenly realized that the instead, our future will have to come to terms increasingly with those very little immaterial things such as water, crops, oil.
All things which, look at it, can certainly be transported from one place to another on earth but are in any case absolutely linked to a circumscribed space, to a territory.
So whoever happens to be sovereign certainly has many more cards than someone who is not, someone who has the misfortune of living in a place with no crops, no oil and no water.
I come to the second novelty which, however, heralds a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this regard, the economic crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritative leadership, the request for someone who knows how to take the situation in hand.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for the existing leaderships, especially the economic ones, which have proved so inadequate and full of gray areas.
And at the same time something even deeper and in a certain sense disturbing: a discredit, an intolerance, an image of inadequacy, a sense of distance, which tends to involve the entire ruling class in a growing number of Western countries.
In other words, the conviction that before their actions are the same ideas of the social elites in vogue up to now, their way of feeling and being, their culture in the general meaning of the term seems to be gaining ground in vast sectors of the population , to have outlived its time and to be increasingly alien to the opinions of the majority.
In short, the request for leadership subtly feeds a ramified but powerful movement of delegitimization of the ruling classes and traditional political structures, which manifests itself in the sudden electoral &quot;riots&quot; or in the sudden changes in the collective moods of recent and very recent times, from conservative rise in Austria-Bavaria to the collapse of Labor consensus in Great Britain, to the rebellion of American congressmen against Bush (and perhaps even the victory of the right in Italy has something to do with it).
One gets the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programmes, but also their rituals, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their formats, some would say, are finding it increasingly difficult to understand, and therefore to represent , what is not taking shape in the deep layers of Western societies from today and which the economic crisis reinvigorates, increases, potentially agitates to excess.
Given all this, to speak of a &quot;revolt of the masses&quot; on the agenda would be frankly exaggerated.
But keeping your eyes peeled certainly isn&#39;t.
