&quot;The glue principle can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged like a stack of spaghetti,&quot; explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
Scientists were inspired by the legs of geckos, covered with microscopic hairs that manage to ensure a perfect adherence to the animal.
Tests conducted on different materials, such as glass, Teflon and sandpaper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful than the paws of these reptiles and at the same time &quot;detaches easily from the wall,&quot; explains Liming Dai, a researcher at the faculty of University of Dayton Engineering.
WALKING ON WALLS? -&quot;This material could be useful as a transitional adhesive,&quot; adds Liming Dai.
Maybe to walk on walls just like Spiderman? Perhaps yes, but researchers are thinking of a much less fascinating use such as the connection between electronic devices, because carbon nanotubes are conductors of heat and electric current.
Other applications could be in aerospace engineering.
No superheroes yet.
