Students who are victims of high rents of up to 900 euros for a room
The rental market for university students knows no crisis.
According to the latest survey by Sunia, the tenants&#39; union, taking a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
&quot;The phenomenon has now assumed very serious characteristics to the point of excluding entire groups of young people from the right to study due to the very high overall costs that the families of origin would have to bear - explains the head of the Sunia research office, Laura Mariani - in these cities the strong demand from students has distorted the market so much as to trigger a generalized increase process also for residents&quot;.
In the majority of cases, the rental offers also contain a series of violations: unregistered, unregistered contracts with no rental limit, connected sub-rentals.
Extraordinary interventions are needed for Sunia which, through the revision of the taxation, can control prices.
Looking at the details of the survey, we see that in Milan, about 450 euros are needed for a bed in the Brianza area; for a single room it ranges from a minimum of 650 (Bande Nere area) to an average value of 800 (Lambiate, Udine and Fiera area) to a maximum of 900 (in the Vittoria area).
In Florence, a bed costs on average 350/400 euros, a room around 700.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in the areas close to the University, 250/280 euros are needed for a bed in a double room, from 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, in areas close to the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), around 600 euros are asked for a single room, 450 for a bed in a double room.
Only slightly lower values (550 euros for a single room) in areas close to other universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
You save only if you move to peripheral areas: 300 euros for a bed and 450 for a single room in Prenestina, Centocelle and similar areas.
In Naples you need 300/450 euros for a bed, for a room you spend between 400 and 600 euros, with the highest prices in the Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei areas.
In Bari you need 250/350 euros for a bed, at least 350 for a single.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they carry more weight in the city&#39;s economy.
Finally, in cities where the phenomenon of renting to non-EU students is more frequent, such as Perugia, a further anomaly is recorded: the increase of about 25/30% of the rent asked of foreign students compared to that applied to Italians.
Goodbye old cinema Paradiso, the cities are canceling the historic cinemas
Historic movie theaters close in favor of multiplexes.
&quot;A city without cinemas is a blind city, it&#39;s like a face without eyes&quot;.
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively photographs what is happening in the large Italian urban centers but also in the cities of the province.
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth of large multiplexes in the suburbs and the consequent death through consumption of single-screens in the central areas of cities, is one of those events that appear to us inescapable and incontrovertible, but which also has all the characteristics of a real own cultural crime.
What often disappears are historical places full of memories, &quot;it is as if a friend were missing, an acquaintance with whom we shared a part of the road and so many emotions&quot;, observes the director of Nuovo cinema Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago earned Tornatore the Academy Award and the Grand Prix of the Cannes jury, and which told the poetry of a provincial cinema and the nostalgia for a way of experiencing cinema lost perhaps forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of exhibitors, speak for themselves: in the last five years 316 traditional cinemas have closed their doors, and the cinemas in the main cities are paying the greatest price: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures, Emilia-Romagna excels with 82 single-screen cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And demonstrating that the advent of the multiplexes is primarily responsible for their disappearance, these are precisely the three Italian regions that recorded the largest number of new multiplex cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy over the last five years, 81 both in Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
«The Italian exhibition has developed irrationally» observes Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, &quot;it is useful to build new structures but the survival of the existing ones should be guaranteed, because when a city hall closes, not all of its visitors are willing to move to multiplexes.
Not to mention the lack of allocation for the fund in favor of the exhibitors: the state&#39;s past debt is around 10 million euros.
It is shameful, from an ethical and moral point of view, that the Government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros a year would be needed».
The case of Bologna is interesting, the first Italian city which, worried about closures, decided to take measures by signing a protocol between the Municipality and Anec, the first of this type in Italy, to protect and promote single-screen cinemas both in the historic center and in the suburbs.
Among the envisaged rules there are tax relief measures in favor of managers and advantages for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area and will have special rates for parking and in some car parks.
&quot;I like this initiative&quot; observes Giuseppe Tornatore &quot;and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by setting up other measures.
It is certain, however, that to counter the overwhelming power of multiplexes, traditional cinemas must also improve the quality of sound and image, because today&#39;s audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is an issue that has always been important to me: the closure of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make &quot;Nuovo cinema Paradiso&quot;, which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass in front of the now closed Rialto or Quirinale in via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many shared emotions, I turn away in order not to see the billboards blackened by dust».
Links between politics and the &#39;Ndrangheta arrested mayor of Gioia Tauro
&quot;The mayor of Gioia Tauro was available to align the choices of the Municipality with the interests of the Piromalli gang&quot;.
The accusations that the magistrates of the Anti-Mafia Directorate of Calabria make against the mayor and deputy mayor of Gioia Tauro Giorgio Dal Torrione and Rosario Schiavone, and the mayor of Rosarno Carlo Martelli, arrested this morning for external competition in a mafia association, are heavy.
Also in handcuffs are Gioacchino Piromalli, the elderly mediator between the clan and the public administrations, and his lawyer nephew, namesake of the boss, already convicted of mafia-type criminal association, sentenced to pay 10 million euros.
&quot;In defiance of any legal and moral norm, as well as common sense&quot;, write the prosecutors, the two local administrations had expressed their willingness to pay lawyer Piromalli for consultancy.
&quot;The gang would thus have been allowed - the judges wrote - to officially enter the town halls, facilitating the already considerable possibilities of control and direction of the public administration&quot;.
The president of the Calabrian regional council Agazio Loiero does not hide that &quot;there are many collusions between local authorities and organized crime&quot; in his region: &quot;There are areas where the mafia intensity is stronger than in others, where collusion is almost inevitable .
But there are many local politicians who resist the pressure of the &#39;Ndrangheta, heroes who keep clean&quot;.
This morning&#39;s arrests follow those of last July in which the police announced that they had beheaded the Piromalli clan.
Since the end of last April, the municipal council of Gioia Tauro had been dissolved but already in 1991, and again due to alleged influences between organized crime and local administration, local politicians had been relieved of their task of administering the municipality.
Giorgio Dal Torrione, mayor of the UDC at the time of its dissolution, had been elected to head a centre-right coalition after the May 2006 runoff.
He cried foul when the Prefecture ordered the dissolution of the city council.
He called into question the then Deputy Minister of the Interior Marco Minniti, accusing him of having engineered everything for a political matter, but the judges, in the arrest warrant signed this morning, explain that the Piromalli gang had even gone so far as to ask for a variation of the project of the A3.
From the interceptions ordered against Dal Torrione, the prosecutors write, emerged &quot;the willingness to marry the needs of an entrepreneur, representative of a larger group notoriously close to the Piromalli, aligning the choices of the public administration with the interests of the gang&quot;.
When energy comes from the waves now the big names take the field
It is an immense deposit, which occupies over 70% of the planet&#39;s surface and is now being discovered by the world&#39;s major energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources on which giants like Chevron have set their sights, and are now trying to get their hands on it.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for the past one hundred years and in the 1970s, coinciding with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell in the 1980s, the idea of harnessing marine energy was shelved, but now environmental concerns and the new rise in oil are boosting the industry.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15 percent of the world&#39;s electricity needs could be covered by plants that exploit the wave motion of the seas.
This amount would be double that currently produced by nuclear power plants.
Plus there would be currents and tides.
Colossus on the attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a plant in northern Portugal.
When the deal was announced it seemed like a revolutionary step.
Two years on, more and more are betting on marine energy and among these are companies that have always devoted themselves to traditional energy.
&quot;Chevron is studying ocean energy technologies - said the spokesman of a company associated with the US oil giant to the Wall Street Journal business newspaper - and is evaluating the possibility of cooperating with us&quot;.
The cooperation in question concerns obtaining a permit from the US Energy Commission, necessary to start a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
This is no small sign, above all if one considers that the US continues to extract oil in Alaska and recently President Bush has launched a plan for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, there are Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey which are following the path of energy that comes from the sea and the sums invested so far, although not known in detail, according to observers indicate an interest on the rise.
Technology to be developed.
Experts speak of a technology still in its infancy, also because marine energy does not dispel all doubts about the environmental impact.
For now, plants such as the Portuguese one or some in Scotland are small and do not seem to create major problems for the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, however, technologies with a greater environmental impact must be used.
And the choices are different: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of connected buoys.
The buoyancy of the waves, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure by pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure spins a turbine which in turn powers a generator.
Electricity is sent ashore via submarine cables.
For now there are four plants of this type in the planning stage, awaiting federal approval and part of the energy could be used for a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces power for a shopping mall and parking lot using six underwater turbines in New York&#39;s East River.
The movement of water when there are tides spins turbine blades, creating a rotary motion that powers a generator.
Verdant said it has a long list of customers awaiting the necessary permits to use the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
Of particular interest, say the Institute for Research of Electricity, deserves the potential of the tides at this time.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable than wind, sun or waves and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
It is precisely on tidal energy that states such as New York, Maine and Alaska, together with others bordering the coasts, have already invested 7 and a half million dollars in 2008 and planned investments of up to 35 million for 2009.
